{"term": "2013", "caseName": "Riley v. California", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/13-132", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - April 29, 2014", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23523", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 13-132, Riley v. California.", "start": 0, "stop": 5.668, "duration": 5.67}, {"text": "Mr. Fisher?", "start": 5.668, "stop": 10.372, "duration": 4.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 10.372, "stop": 16.526, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "This case involves applying the core protection of the Fourth Amendment to a new factual circumstance.", "start": 16.526, "stop": 22.613, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "It has always been the case that an occasion of an arrest did not give the police officers authority to search through the private papers and the drawers and bureaus and cabinets of somebody's house, and that protection should not evaporate more than 200 years after the founding because we have the technological development of smartphones that have resulted in people carrying that information in their pockets.", "start": 22.613, "stop": 44.46, "duration": 21.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just -- just to test the principle for why the police can search and seize some -- some objects.", "start": 44.46, "stop": 52.566, "duration": 8.11}, {"text": "Consider a gun.", "start": 52.566, "stop": 54.283, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "The arrestee has a gun on his person and the police take the gun.", "start": 54.283, "stop": 59.22, "duration": 4.94}, {"text": "Is part of the reason for that seizure to obtain evidence of the crime or is it just for the safety of the officer and the safety of the community?", "start": 59.22, "stop": 70.277, "duration": 11.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what this Court said in Robinson at Page 235 is the reason supporting the authority for a search incident to arrest are the two Chimel factors, which are gathering evidence to prevent its destruction, and officer's safety.", "start": 70.277, "stop": 84.687, "duration": 14.41}, {"text": "Now--", "start": 84.687, "stop": 85.254, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about gathering evidence in order to make the case?", "start": 85.254, "stop": 89.156, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "For instance, with the gun, could they take fingerprints?", "start": 89.156, "stop": 93.308, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "The -- the gun is in the police station where the arrestee is being booked.", "start": 93.308, "stop": 97.428, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "A, could they take fingerprints?", "start": 97.428, "stop": 99.178, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "B, could they copy the serial number?", "start": 99.178, "stop": 101.047, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "C, could they see how many shells were left in the chamber?", "start": 101.047, "stop": 105.116, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "They obviously have to empty it for safety purposes.", "start": 105.116, "stop": 106.883, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "All for the purpose of building the case, of -- of obtaining evidence?", "start": 106.883, "stop": 112.437, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, of course that's done every day.", "start": 112.437, "stop": 115.723, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "Once the gun is in the police -- the police department's lawful possession, I think Edwards says that they can do all that.", "start": 115.723, "stop": 121.71, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "So -- so if -- if the proposition then, if the principle then is that some objects that are obtained from the arrestee can be examined in order to build the State's case, is that at least a beginning premise that we can accept in your case, although, obviously, there are problems of the extent and intrusiveness of the search that are -- are your case, but not in the gun hypothetical.", "start": 121.71, "stop": 149.979, "duration": 28.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Justice Kennedy, the Court has never described that as one of the things.", "start": 149.979, "stop": 154.264, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "If you want to think about this case the way you thought about the automobile search in Gant, it would be a beginning premise; but I think you're right, that even if that were a beginning premise, it would be only that, a beginning.", "start": 154.264, "stop": 165.072, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "In Footnote 9 in Edwards, this Court said that any search incident to arrest still has to satisfy the Fourth Amendment's general -- general reasonableness.", "start": 165.072, "stop": 173.01, "duration": 7.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think you're right that Gant is probably the best statement in support of the principle that I've -- I've suggested, and then you might say, well, that's limited to automobiles--", "start": 173.01, "stop": 183.884, "duration": 10.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 183.884, "stop": 184.101, "duration": 0.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and then we're back where we started.", "start": 184.101, "stop": 184.969, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 184.969, "stop": 185.452, "duration": 0.48}, {"text": "And there's important things to understand if you want to start thinking about Gant, because both in terms of its history and its modern application, it's dramatically different from what we have here.", "start": 185.452, "stop": 196.275, "duration": 10.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Fisher, before we do that, have you been accurate in what you said about Robinson and about the Court's cases?", "start": 196.275, "stop": 204.714, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "In Weeks, which was quoted in Robinson, the Court said:", "start": 204.714, "stop": 209.251, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "\"The right, always recognized under English and American law, to search the person of the accused when legally arrested to discover and seize the fruits or evidences of crime. \"", "start": 209.251, "stop": 222.509, "duration": 13.26}, {"text": "Is that historically inaccurate?", "start": 222.509, "stop": 225.545, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "Do you want us to repudiate that?", "start": 225.545, "stop": 228.162, "duration": 2.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Your Honor.", "start": 228.162, "stop": 229.581, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "What Weeks said, you quoted it, fruits and instrumentalities of the crime have always been something that could be seized from a person.", "start": 229.581, "stop": 238.62, "duration": 9.04}, {"text": "Now, Weeks, of course, as this Court said in Robinson itself, was dicta.", "start": 238.62, "stop": 242.322, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "And there was that historical authority to take fruits and evidence -- I'm sorry -- fruits and instrumentalities of the crime.", "start": 242.322, "stop": 249.66, "duration": 7.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did it say instrumentalities or evidence?", "start": 249.66, "stop": 251.345, "duration": 1.69}, {"text": "Which did it say?", "start": 251.345, "stop": 252.245, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Weeks used--", "start": 252.245, "stop": 252.947, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because Justice Alito said evidence.", "start": 252.947, "stop": 254.33, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "You -- you changed it to instrumentality.", "start": 254.33, "stop": 257.099, "duration": 2.77}, {"text": "Is one of you wrong?", "start": 257.099, "stop": 258.049, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Weeks uses the word “ evidence ”, but, Justice Scalia, because it was not at issue in that case, the -- the Bishop treatise that you cited in your Thornton concurrence talks about tools and instrumentalities.", "start": 258.049, "stop": 269.223, "duration": 11.17}, {"text": "Now, I don't think we have to debate that here, because even if we're in a world where the police can seize some evidence and keep it and use it for the prosecution simply for that reason, even if they don't fear destruction, there are still very, very profound problems with searching a smartphone without a warrant, because even under the Robinson rule, this Court has recognized, for example, when it comes to blood draws, search -- something like a strip search that might occur at the scene, there are limits even to the Robinson rule.", "start": 269.223, "stop": 296.641, "duration": 27.42}, {"text": "So it brings us--", "start": 296.641, "stop": 297.907, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, smartphones -- smartphones do present difficult problems.", "start": 297.907, "stop": 300.526, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "But let me ask you this: Suppose your client were an old-school guy and he didn't have -- he didn't have a cell phone.", "start": 300.526, "stop": 307.363, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "He had a billfold and he had photos that were important to him in the billfold.", "start": 307.363, "stop": 314.353, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "He had that at the time of arrest.", "start": 314.353, "stop": 316.786, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "Do you dispute the proposition that the police could examine the photos in his billfold and use those as evidence against him?", "start": 316.786, "stop": 325.908, "duration": 9.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 325.908, "stop": 326.426, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "That's the rule of Robinson, that any physical item on a arrestee can be seized and inspected and then used as evidence if it's useful evidence.", "start": 326.426, "stop": 335.782, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "We draw a line.", "start": 335.782, "stop": 336.732, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 336.732, "stop": 337.166, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "What is the difference between looking at hardcopy photos in a billfold and looking at photos that are saved in the memory of a cell phone?", "start": 337.166, "stop": 347.24, "duration": 10.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "The difference is digital information versus physical items.", "start": 347.24, "stop": 350.959, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "Physical items at the scene can pose a safety threat and have destruction possibilities that aren't present with digital evidence.", "start": 350.959, "stop": 358.046, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "What is more, once you get into the digital world, you have the framers' concern of general warrants and the -- the writs of assistance.", "start": 358.046, "stop": 366.468, "duration": 8.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, how does that apply -- how does that apply to these hardcopy photos in the billfold?", "start": 366.468, "stop": 370.439, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "They don't present a threat to anybody.", "start": 370.439, "stop": 372.722, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "And I don't see that there's much of a difference between -- the government argues there's a greater risk of the destruction of digital evidence in a cell phone than -- than there is in the photos.", "start": 372.722, "stop": 385.282, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "So I don't quite understand how -- how that applies to that situation.", "start": 385.282, "stop": 390.167, "duration": 4.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let me take those one thing at a time.", "start": 390.167, "stop": 391.769, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "I take it the theory of Robinson, this is the theory the government itself propounded, is that any physical item, because it contained a razor blade or a pin or anything, needs to be inspected to be sure.", "start": 391.769, "stop": 402.141, "duration": 10.37}, {"text": "And so you have a categorical rule because of the ad hoc nature of arrests that police don't have to distinguish physical items one from the other.", "start": 402.141, "stop": 409.23, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but the -- but in the wallet -- we'll just stick with Justice Alito's hypothetical -- they find a business card or something which shows a car rental service.", "start": 409.23, "stop": 419.453, "duration": 10.22}, {"text": "Can they turn the card over and read it?", "start": 419.453, "stop": 421.555, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "They're not looking for a pin or an explosive.", "start": 421.555, "stop": 423.907, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "They're trying to read what's on the card.", "start": 423.907, "stop": 425.49, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "Can they do that?", "start": 425.49, "stop": 427.609, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think they can, if nothing else, under plain view once it's in their hand, Justice Kennedy.", "start": 427.609, "stop": 432.178, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "But I really don't want to fight--", "start": 432.178, "stop": 433.613, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, they turn -- they turn the card over.", "start": 433.613, "stop": 435.382, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that is fine under the categorical rule.", "start": 435.382, "stop": 439.434, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "I think what you have in Robinson is a categorical rule that obviates these exact difficult case-by-case determinations.", "start": 439.434, "stop": 445.853, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "You can make an argument, and if I needed to, if it were a diary case or a billfold case, you might be able to make an argument, but I think the Court wisely decided under Robinson that we need a categorical rule that's easily administrable in the field.", "start": 445.853, "stop": 458.061, "duration": 12.21}, {"text": "Now, when you have digital evidence, the categorical rule, we submit, cuts exactly in the opposite direction.", "start": 458.061, "stop": 463.299, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "Because digital information -- even the notion of flipping through photos in a smartphone implicates vast amounts of information, not just the photos themselves, but the GPS locational data that's linked in with it, all kinds of other information that is intrinsically intertwined in smartphones.", "start": 463.299, "stop": 480.76, "duration": 17.46}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Including information that is specifically designed to be made public.", "start": 480.76, "stop": 484.728, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "I mean, what about something like Facebook or a Twitter account?", "start": 484.728, "stop": 488.097, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "There's no real -- there's no -- any privacy interest in a Facebook account is at least diminished because the point is you want these things to be public and seen widely.", "start": 488.097, "stop": 496.62, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Chief Justice--", "start": 496.62, "stop": 498.222, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So I guess my question would be: Could you have a rule that the police are entitled to search those apps that, in fact, don't have an air of privacy about them?", "start": 498.222, "stop": 506.561, "duration": 8.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that would be extraordinarily difficult to administer that rule.", "start": 506.561, "stop": 510.113, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "And let me tell you why.", "start": 510.113, "stop": 511.063, "duration": 0.95}, {"text": "Because most of the information on smartphones is private.", "start": 511.063, "stop": 515.434, "duration": 4.37}, {"text": "Much of it is just, like the photos in this case, just kept on somebody's phone and not shared with anybody.", "start": 515.434, "stop": 520.219, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "Even a Facebook account is a limited universe of people who have access to it.", "start": 520.219, "stop": 524.789, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "You're right that--", "start": 524.789, "stop": 526.022, "duration": 1.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "More -- more or less limited.", "start": 526.022, "stop": 527.241, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "I mean, you know, maybe it's 20 people; maybe it's a hundred people.", "start": 527.241, "stop": 530.593, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "But it's certainly not private in the sense that many of the other applications are.", "start": 530.593, "stop": 535.061, "duration": 4.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think it's fair to say you have a sliding scale and there's some stuff on a phone that might be posted on the Internet, for example.", "start": 535.061, "stop": 541.582, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "The difficulty with that case, if you wanted to address it in a future case, would be the intertwined nature of information on a phone.", "start": 541.582, "stop": 548.905, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "So looking at those photos in a smartphone account will be linked to the contacts inside the phone; it will be linked to GPS information inside the phone.", "start": 548.905, "stop": 556.259, "duration": 7.35}, {"text": "All of this information is intertwined and I think you'd have a difficult administrability problem if you wanted to create some sort of rule like that.", "start": 556.259, "stop": 563.997, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "Now, remember, the government might try to deal with that problem differently by saying information in the cloud, so to speak, is not accessible to officers.", "start": 563.997, "stop": 571.836, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "We submit that just further would compound the difficulty of applying a rule in this circumstance.", "start": 571.836, "stop": 577.674, "duration": 5.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But do you think in this case we have to decide whether all the information that may be available in a smartphone can be examined by the police when the owner of the phone is arrested or can we just focus on the particular evidence that was admitted in your client's trial?", "start": 577.674, "stop": 595.536, "duration": 17.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the way you've phrased the question, I think that's what -- that's the first cut at this, is looking at the particular pieces of evidence here, which are photos and videos.", "start": 595.536, "stop": 605.091, "duration": 9.56}, {"text": "But we don't think you can write an opinion that would distinguish those from anything else on a -- almost anything else on a smartphone.", "start": 605.091, "stop": 613.247, "duration": 8.16}, {"text": "I mean, the State's argument here is that those are not, quote, “ fundamentally different ” from other things that people would carry around.", "start": 613.247, "stop": 619.501, "duration": 6.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you think you could have obtained a warrant -- or that the police could have obtained a warrant in this case?", "start": 619.501, "stop": 623.553, "duration": 4.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "In all likelihood, yes, Justice Kennedy.", "start": 623.553, "stop": 625.488, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 625.488, "stop": 625.838, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "They had plenty of time to do so.", "start": 625.838, "stop": 626.921, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, then the evidence that's seizable under the warrant is -- is reasonable, and Justice Alito points out the fact that some of this evidence is -- is reasonable.", "start": 626.921, "stop": 640.248, "duration": 13.33}, {"text": "If there's a -- there's a limitation with reference to the way the police behaved, as Justice Alito points out, it's limited just to this evidence.", "start": 640.248, "stop": 650.203, "duration": 9.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let me say a couple important things about the warrant requirement and return to Justice Alito's question.", "start": 650.203, "stop": 655.507, "duration": 5.3}, {"text": "This Court has said time and again that the mere fact the police could have gotten a warrant but didn't does not excuse a Fourth Amendment violation.", "start": 655.507, "stop": 662.528, "duration": 7.02}, {"text": "Let me say a couple things about the warrant requirement and then return to Justice Alito.", "start": 662.528, "stop": 666.648, "duration": 4.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but it -- it just goes to the fact that this -- that this is searchable under Fourth Amendment standards.", "start": 666.648, "stop": 673.902, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "With a warrant, Justice Kennedy.", "start": 673.902, "stop": 675.838, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "And let me talk about why a warrant is so important.", "start": 675.838, "stop": 677.94, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "First of all, it interposes a neutral observer in between the citizen and the police officer.", "start": 677.94, "stop": 684.026, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "Perhaps more importantly, it does two very big things.", "start": 684.026, "stop": 687.645, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "One is it can trigger the Fourth Amendment's particularity requirement so that the magistrate can say: This is what you can look at and what didn't.", "start": 687.645, "stop": 694.815, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "Remember, in this case the prosecution ultimately introduced photos and videos, but that's not what the detective testified to at trial as to the scope of his search.", "start": 694.815, "stop": 704.007, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "He said, at JA-11, we looked at a whole lot of stuff on the phone and that's just what, in his words, “ caught his eye ”.", "start": 704.007, "stop": 711.261, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "So how -- how would it work with a magistrate?", "start": 711.261, "stop": 714.379, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "You recognize -- you just told Justice Kennedy -- that a warrant could be obtained.", "start": 714.379, "stop": 722.735, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "A warrant for what?", "start": 722.735, "stop": 724.469, "duration": 1.73}, {"text": "What would the police have to show?", "start": 724.469, "stop": 728.722, "duration": 4.25}, {"text": "And let's take your very case.", "start": 728.722, "stop": 730.574, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "So they -- they have seized, which is proper, seized the phone, they've secured it, and now they want to search it.", "start": 730.574, "stop": 740.28, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "So they apply for a warrant.", "start": 740.28, "stop": 742.465, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "And what would the warrant have to say?", "start": 742.465, "stop": 744.132, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "We give an example of a warrant in the footnote in our reply brief.", "start": 744.132, "stop": 748.452, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "I believe it's footnote 3, Justice Ginsburg.", "start": 748.452, "stop": 750.336, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "And there are many more available on the web from States that already require warrants.", "start": 750.336, "stop": 755.206, "duration": 4.87}, {"text": "What they do is they say -- the police officer testifies, perhaps somewhat like he testified here at the suppression hearing, I suspected this fellow was in a gang and -- and I believe gang members keep certain kinds of things on their phone, this is the kind of crime that we're investigating, and therefore these particular files within the phone are likely to obtain evidence.", "start": 755.206, "stop": 775.536, "duration": 20.33}, {"text": "And then what happens is the warrants say with particularity: Here's the things you can look at; here's what you can't.", "start": 775.536, "stop": 780.923, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "More importantly, Justice Ginsburg, a warrant requirement--", "start": 780.923, "stop": 784.125, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought you say that's very -- you've told us that that's -- that's hard to figure out, what you can and what you can't.", "start": 784.125, "stop": 789.027, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "But it's easy for a magistrate, but -- but impossible for a -- for an arresting officer?", "start": 789.027, "stop": 796.2, "duration": 7.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think much easier for a magistrate at some remove than an officer under the -- under the stresses in the field.", "start": 796.2, "stop": 804.121, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "Now, Justice Scalia--", "start": 804.121, "stop": 805.139, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but--", "start": 805.139, "stop": 805.622, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I agree, it's not going to be perfect.", "start": 805.622, "stop": 807.324, "duration": 1.7}, {"text": "And so let's look at what happens under our world--", "start": 807.324, "stop": 809.524, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If I could just--", "start": 809.524, "stop": 809.907, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 809.907, "stop": 810.442, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--on the same lines as -- as Justice Scalia.", "start": 810.442, "stop": 812.276, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "The point you make elsewhere in your brief and argument is that the cell phone or the -- the smartphone has everything.", "start": 812.276, "stop": 818.28, "duration": 6}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 818.28, "stop": 818.663, "duration": 0.38}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's got the person's whole life.", "start": 818.663, "stop": 819.882, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "Well, if you're arresting somebody on the grounds of suspicion that he's a gang member and you have evidence to support that, what part of the smartphone is not likely to have pertinent evidence?", "start": 819.882, "stop": 830.354, "duration": 10.47}, {"text": "What application is not?", "start": 830.354, "stop": 832.206, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "I mean, here you've got pictures, you've got videos, you've got calls.", "start": 832.206, "stop": 835.325, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "I just -- I guess it's similar to what other issues have been raised.", "start": 835.325, "stop": 839.377, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "I don't know what a magistrate is supposed to put in the warrant.", "start": 839.377, "stop": 842.412, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say his banking app, his online dating app--", "start": 842.412, "stop": 846.63, "duration": 4.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't think his banking app -- his banking app is going to say on this day he deposited $10,000 into his account, and then that's going to coincide with a particular drug deal.", "start": 846.63, "stop": 854.986, "duration": 8.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Mr. Chief Justice, those arguments can be made on an app-by-app basis.", "start": 854.986, "stop": 859.872, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "But what happens is -- this is the benefit of our rule as opposed to the government's.", "start": 859.872, "stop": 864.258, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "What the government says is let the officer look and then have a back-end hearing where you just suppress all the stuff that he wasn't supposed to look at once you apply particularity requirements.", "start": 864.258, "stop": 873.447, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "Under our rule, once the officer has the warrant, Leon kicks in and so you don't have to have all these hearings in district courts, because once an officer does a proper search according to the corners of a warrant, you don't have to have the kind of suppression here.", "start": 873.447, "stop": 886.355, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "And there's one other very important thing that goes into a warrant which might have been glossed over too quickly in the briefs.", "start": 886.355, "stop": 892.425, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "It's not just what can be looked at; it's how it can be kept.", "start": 892.425, "stop": 896.143, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "The retention of information raises extraordinary Fourth Amendment concerns.", "start": 896.143, "stop": 901.864, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "My understanding in California is, at least for some crimes, it's not just that they're downloading the information and looking at it for the crime of arrest, but they're keeping this information in databases, ever-growing databases of every cell phone that they've ever seized.", "start": 901.864, "stop": 915.957, "duration": 14.09}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if you have a device that doesn't have the broad information that a smartphone has, but only a very limited, like a Fitbit that tells you how many steps you've taken, and the defendant says, I've been in my house all afternoon, and they want to check and see if he's walked 4 miles.", "start": 915.957, "stop": 931.817, "duration": 15.86}, {"text": "It's not his whole life, which is a big part of your objection.", "start": 931.817, "stop": 934.852, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "Is that something they can look at?", "start": 934.852, "stop": 936.453, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think probably not.", "start": 936.453, "stop": 937.987, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "And I think this is the way the categorical rule in Robinson, where it sweeps in the kind of hypotheticals we were talking about in one direction.", "start": 937.987, "stop": 944.543, "duration": 6.56}, {"text": "I think a categorical rule in the other direction for digital information would sweep in the Fitbit.", "start": 944.543, "stop": 949.711, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "I mean, obviously, I don't have to win that argument today, but I think that's how you would approach that question.", "start": 949.711, "stop": 955.682, "duration": 5.97}, {"text": "Remember, the Fitbit -- and this is true even more so of smartphones -- tells you just the kind of information the Court was very concerned about in Kyllo.", "start": 955.682, "stop": 963.355, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "It tells you -- modern smartphones work the inside of people's house.", "start": 963.355, "stop": 968.075, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "They work the appliances and -- and they have cameras.", "start": 968.075, "stop": 971.211, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "They also monitor the inside of people's bodies.", "start": 971.211, "stop": 974.313, "duration": 3.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if the phone in this case was an old-fashioned flip-phone?", "start": 974.313, "stop": 978.88, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "So it had the capacity to take pictures, but a much more limited memory.", "start": 978.88, "stop": 983.934, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "Would it -- would it be a different case?", "start": 983.934, "stop": 985.786, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think you may want to -- that will be part of your conversation in the next case perhaps.", "start": 985.786, "stop": 990.588, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "I think the easiest way to decide the case right now in 2014 is simply say: Digital evidence kept on modern cell phones are different than physical items.", "start": 990.588, "stop": 1003.748, "duration": 13.16}, {"text": "I don't think it's really worth going back in time to the most rudimentary device and having that argument.", "start": 1003.748, "stop": 1009.736, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if the person had on his person a compact disk with photos saved on that?", "start": 1009.736, "stop": 1015.489, "duration": 5.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that might be the same kind of case as you have now.", "start": 1015.489, "stop": 1020.107, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "Remember, the -- the phone in this case had a removable memory card, as many still do, which by the way we were going to talk about the destruction of evidence.", "start": 1020.107, "stop": 1030.649, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "That's one answer to the destruction of evidence problem.", "start": 1030.649, "stop": 1033.017, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "It couldn't possibly have arisen with respect to the evidence at issue because it was on a removable memory card that couldn't be erased remotely or password protected.", "start": 1033.017, "stop": 1041.138, "duration": 8.12}, {"text": "Now, we've given lots of arguments in the brief that explain why the government's arguments as to wiping simply don't stand up.", "start": 1041.138, "stop": 1049.977, "duration": 8.84}, {"text": "And--", "start": 1049.977, "stop": 1050.393, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fisher, would you -- an earlier question, you didn't finish the answer.", "start": 1050.393, "stop": 1055.462, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "You were describing a difference between the downloading by police into databases that they keep forever.", "start": 1055.462, "stop": 1062.551, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "What happens with materials that are returned pursuant to a search warrant?", "start": 1062.551, "stop": 1067.27, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "Are they precluded from doing that?", "start": 1067.27, "stop": 1068.622, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 1068.622, "stop": 1069.472, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I wasn't sure I understood your--", "start": 1069.472, "stop": 1071.24, "duration": 1.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1071.24, "stop": 1071.606, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "So I take it that the ordinary rule is if the police lawfully seize evidence in the physical world, if it's a -- if it's a physical item, it might at some point have to be returned to the owner of it.", "start": 1071.606, "stop": 1082.196, "duration": 10.59}, {"text": "But if it's something that can be made a photocopy of or a photo, it remains in police files as lawfully obtained information they can use indefinitely into the future.", "start": 1082.196, "stop": 1091.57, "duration": 9.37}, {"text": "You have real problems, however, when you apply that typical rule to digital information, because now -- again, what I understand -- and the government itself -- the Federal Government in Footnote 3 of its reply brief in Wurie acknowledges that it's keeping in an ever-growing Federal database at least some of the information seized from smartphones.", "start": 1091.57, "stop": 1113.917, "duration": 22.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I'm sorry.", "start": 1113.917, "stop": 1114.367, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "I don't know that you've answered my question.", "start": 1114.367, "stop": 1115.935, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 1115.935, "stop": 1116.352, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "Maybe I didn't understand it.", "start": 1116.352, "stop": 1116.852, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which -- can they do the same thing once a search warrant is--", "start": 1116.852, "stop": 1119.304, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh.", "start": 1119.304, "stop": 1119.571, "duration": 0.27}, {"text": "No.", "start": 1119.571, "stop": 1119.971, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "Well, not necessarily, because the beauty of a search warrant is it can delineate retention rules.", "start": 1119.971, "stop": 1127.31, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "It can say here's -- here's how long you're allowed to keep the information, here's who's allowed to look at it and who's not.", "start": 1127.31, "stop": 1132.714, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "And it can--", "start": 1132.714, "stop": 1133.631, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Frankly, I have to tell you, I don't ever remember a prosecutor coming to me with that kind of delineation.", "start": 1133.631, "stop": 1141.92, "duration": 8.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I think that, Justice Sotomayor, that is what is starting to now happen in the digital world, because we just have new and different concerns that had arisen -- than had arisen in the past.", "start": 1141.92, "stop": 1151.009, "duration": 9.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fisher, would there be exigencies that would allow police to look at cell phones?", "start": 1151.009, "stop": 1155.66, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "And if so, what would those exigencies be?", "start": 1155.66, "stop": 1157.946, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Absolutely.", "start": 1157.946, "stop": 1158.912, "duration": 0.97}, {"text": "There -- there would be times at the scene where exigencies would allow it.", "start": 1158.912, "stop": 1164.516, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "First of all, the two officer safety arguments the other side makes about a hypothetical bomb or a confederate ambush, as this Court already recognized in Chadwick, would give exigent circumstances.", "start": 1164.516, "stop": 1174.808, "duration": 10.29}, {"text": "The concern about remote wiping we think, and as the experts have described in the amicus brief filed by EPIC and many others, we don't think would ever arise -- give rise to a situation where that was a legitimate concern, but in a very odd world, yes.", "start": 1174.808, "stop": 1190.068, "duration": 15.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I don't understand your first exigent circumstances.", "start": 1190.068, "stop": 1194.036, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "When there is a bomb, but you can't -- you don't know whether there's a bomb until you look in the phone.", "start": 1194.036, "stop": 1199.423, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "Whether -- whether his associates are on the way to, you know, to kill the officer and -- and release their confederate, you don't know until you look into the phone.", "start": 1199.423, "stop": 1209.897, "duration": 10.47}, {"text": "So how -- you know, how can that possibly be an exigent circumstance?", "start": 1209.897, "stop": 1213.683, "duration": 3.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think surrounding facts and circumstances -- in Footnote 9 in Chadwick, what the Court said, dealing with a locked briefcase where you'd have the same problem, Justice Scalia, surrounding facts and circumstances might indicate.", "start": 1213.683, "stop": 1224.391, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "There's a hypothetical, I believe it's on page 1 of the amicus brief filed by the State investigative agencies, that I think gives a classic textbook example of how exigent circumstances might apply.", "start": 1224.391, "stop": 1234.846, "duration": 10.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "It seems to me it would almost never -- you would never be able to say, you know, surrounding circumstances give me reason to suspect that there's a bomb in the phone.", "start": 1234.846, "stop": 1244.718, "duration": 9.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1244.718, "stop": 1244.884, "duration": 0.17}, {"text": "I--", "start": 1244.884, "stop": 1245.184, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Give me reason to suspect that his confederates are on the way.", "start": 1245.184, "stop": 1248.586, "duration": 3.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think you're right that that's going to be an extraordinarily rare circumstance.", "start": 1248.586, "stop": 1252.738, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "All I'm saying is if you had that extraordinarily rare circumstance, you would not need to get a warrant.", "start": 1252.738, "stop": 1258.309, "duration": 5.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "There -- there is not much authority that I could find, if the lawyer is arrested and -- and they want to read his whole briefcase or you want to read a year's diary.", "start": 1258.309, "stop": 1270.283, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "And you cite -- I think it's page 7 of your brief -- the Learned Hand 1916 case.", "start": 1270.283, "stop": 1277.455, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "Is that about the best discussion you -- you can find?", "start": 1277.455, "stop": 1281.491, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "I didn't find anything much different.", "start": 1281.491, "stop": 1283.509, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Kennedy, we looked high and low as well--", "start": 1283.509, "stop": 1285.476, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 1285.476, "stop": 1285.876, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and did not find cases involving briefcases full of documents.", "start": 1285.876, "stop": 1289.68, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "And there's only one or two stray mentions of a diary.", "start": 1289.68, "stop": 1291.863, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "Judge Friendly also mentions the diary situation.", "start": 1291.863, "stop": 1294.199, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because it's important if we're going to try to formulate some standard which limits the extent of the search, and that's one of -- that's one of the problems in this case.", "start": 1294.199, "stop": 1302.838, "duration": 8.64}, {"text": "If -- if say we rule for the government in its case, maybe it's not quite fair to ask you, but if we rule for the government in its case in Wurie, in the Federal case--", "start": 1302.838, "stop": 1314.978, "duration": 12.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1314.978, "stop": 1315.445, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and there's no -- it's not an exigent circumstances, is there some standard where we could draw the line which would still result in a judgment in -- in your favor?", "start": 1315.445, "stop": 1328.555, "duration": 13.11}, {"text": "Maybe that's not quite a fair question.", "start": 1328.555, "stop": 1330.072, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "You're not -- you're not answering -- you're not arguing the -- the government's case.", "start": 1330.072, "stop": 1333.276, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't want to tread on both lawyers in that case, but certainly in my case, we have an exploratory search where not even the State has contended the amount of information looked at is equivalent to what somebody could have carried around in the old days.", "start": 1333.276, "stop": 1346.1, "duration": 12.82}, {"text": "Can I say something?", "start": 1346.1, "stop": 1346.766, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm going to say something first.", "start": 1346.766, "stop": 1348.816, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 1348.816, "stop": 1349.235, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 1349.235, "stop": 1349.768, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "If -- if the phone rings, can the police answer it?", "start": 1349.768, "stop": 1354.887, "duration": 5.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "There are cases on that, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 1354.887, "stop": 1357.572, "duration": 2.68}, {"text": "Obviously, this Court hasn't addressed them.", "start": 1357.572, "stop": 1359.508, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "All the cases we've found are cases where the police already had a warrant in hand and they've been held that, yes, the police officers can answer the phone in that circumstance.", "start": 1359.508, "stop": 1368.963, "duration": 9.45}, {"text": "Unquestionably, the police officers could look at the screen.", "start": 1368.963, "stop": 1371.998, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Excuse me.", "start": 1371.998, "stop": 1372.448, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "A warrant for what?", "start": 1372.448, "stop": 1373.333, "duration": 0.88}, {"text": "A warrant for examining the phone?", "start": 1373.333, "stop": 1375.35, "duration": 2.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "For somebody's arrest.", "start": 1375.35, "stop": 1375.702, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "For somebody's arrest.", "start": 1375.702, "stop": 1376.769, "duration": 1.07}, {"text": "Well, how does that extend to your ability to answer his phone?", "start": 1376.769, "stop": 1381.104, "duration": 4.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I'm sorry, Mr. Justice Scalia.", "start": 1381.104, "stop": 1382.706, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "I think also in -- to -- to effectuate an arrest and -- and an immediate search of the area.", "start": 1382.706, "stop": 1387.258, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "Now, certainly you could look at the caller ID coming through because that would be in plain view.", "start": 1387.258, "stop": 1393.331, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "But if I can return to Justice Kennedy's question about the diary.", "start": 1393.331, "stop": 1396.883, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "Because there's a couple of important aspects to that I hope to be able to draw out.", "start": 1396.883, "stop": 1401.001, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "The reason I think that you don't find diary cases when you look for them is because people hardly ever carry a diary outside the home with them.", "start": 1401.001, "stop": 1410.29, "duration": 9.29}, {"text": "It was kept in a private drawer in the bedroom or wherever it might be kept, and in the highly, highly unusual circumstance where somebody did, you might have a hard case.", "start": 1410.29, "stop": 1419.646, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "This is an -- this is the opposite world.", "start": 1419.646, "stop": 1422.181, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "The modern reality of smartphones is that it is an indispensable item for everyday life of a modern professional and, indeed, most anyone.", "start": 1422.181, "stop": 1430.77, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "You can't leave the house without it and be -- consider yourself to be responsible and safe.", "start": 1430.77, "stop": 1436.258, "duration": 5.49}, {"text": "And so you take -- to take a world where the police might try to say, we can get the stray diary because of the importance of the categorical rule under Robinson and try to apply that into a world where everybody has everything with them at all times--", "start": 1436.258, "stop": 1451.1, "duration": 14.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, including the criminals who are more dangerous, more sophisticated, more -- more elusive with cell phones.", "start": 1451.1, "stop": 1456.837, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "That's the -- that's the other side of this.", "start": 1456.837, "stop": 1459.123, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Justice Kennedy, the Fourth Amendment has -- has a balance already built in in that respect.", "start": 1459.123, "stop": 1463.858, "duration": 4.73}, {"text": "We're not saying they can't look at digital information.", "start": 1463.858, "stop": 1465.96, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "We're just saying that when they seize it, they can freeze the contents and then go get a warrant and search what they're allowed to search and keep it under the rules of that warrant.", "start": 1465.96, "stop": 1475.399, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it significant in -- in this case that the information was not protected by a password?", "start": 1475.399, "stop": 1479.953, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I don't think either side--", "start": 1479.953, "stop": 1481.77, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That doesn't -- that doesn't affect the expectation of privacy?", "start": 1481.77, "stop": 1484.372, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "--If the other side were making an argument that this wasn't even a search, then I think that might be an argument they would deploy.", "start": 1484.372, "stop": 1491.844, "duration": 7.47}, {"text": "But I think, and I don't want to speak for the government, but I think that they also agree that password protection doesn't matter.", "start": 1491.844, "stop": 1497.914, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "And it certainly doesn't matter under their argument as to what information they get.", "start": 1497.914, "stop": 1501.283, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "I mean, their position is if we seize a corporate executive's smartphone at the scene that is locked and protected under password, if we can get that information out back at our lab, we get it all and we don't have to ask for a warrant and we can keep it as long as we want.", "start": 1501.283, "stop": 1515.543, "duration": 14.26}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1515.543, "stop": 1515.86, "duration": 0.32}, {"text": "I know they argue that it doesn't matter, but I'm just wondering if your position is weakened by the fact that the individual did not seek the greater protection of a password.", "start": 1515.86, "stop": 1524.232, "duration": 8.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I don't think so.", "start": 1524.232, "stop": 1525.449, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "People don't lock their homes, they don't lock their briefcases.", "start": 1525.449, "stop": 1528.201, "duration": 2.75}, {"text": "Simply having it inside the smartphone protected on the person is enough to trigger the Fourth Amendment, and I think to sustain the arguments I've advanced.", "start": 1528.201, "stop": 1536.789, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "If I could reserve the rest of my time.", "start": 1536.789, "stop": 1538.141, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1538.141, "stop": 1539.041, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "Mr. Dumont.", "start": 1539.041, "stop": 1544.629, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1544.629, "stop": 1548.264, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "As Mr. Fisher has said, if Mr. Riley had been carrying physical photographs in his pocket at the time of his arrest, there's no dispute that arresting officers could have looked at those photographs to see whether they contained evidence of crime.", "start": 1548.264, "stop": 1563.607, "duration": 15.34}, {"text": "Now, what would have been reasonable in that situation does not become constitutionally unreasonable simply because Mr. Riley instead carried his photographs in digital form on a smartphone.", "start": 1563.607, "stop": 1575.264, "duration": 11.66}, {"text": "The shifted digital format does not make the photographs any less his papers or effects--", "start": 1575.264, "stop": 1580.318, "duration": 5.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Counsel, in one of our Court decisions in the past, a series of justices asked -- or noted that many of our rules were based on practical considerations.", "start": 1580.318, "stop": 1593.726, "duration": 13.41}, {"text": "Practically speaking, a person can only carry so much on their person.", "start": 1593.726, "stop": 1599.966, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "That is different because carrying a billfold of photographs is a billfold of photographs.", "start": 1599.966, "stop": 1609.488, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "It's, you know, anywhere from one to five generally and not much more.", "start": 1609.488, "stop": 1613.806, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "But now we're talking about potentially thousands, because with digital cameras people take endless photos and it spans their entire life.", "start": 1613.806, "stop": 1624.164, "duration": 10.36}, {"text": "You don't see a difference between the two things?", "start": 1624.164, "stop": 1627.716, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "What -- what has now become impractical.", "start": 1627.716, "stop": 1632.687, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "A GPS can follow people in a way that prior following by police officers in cars didn't permit.", "start": 1632.687, "stop": 1641.207, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--We certainly see a distinction, and we certainly see the possibility that in some cases there could potentially be a constitutional difference.", "start": 1641.207, "stop": 1648.797, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "What we don't see is that in this case -- on the facts of this case or anything like it, like the ordinary case, there is a constitutional difference from those phenomenon.", "start": 1648.797, "stop": 1658.068, "duration": 9.27}, {"text": "The theory--", "start": 1658.068, "stop": 1661.12, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "By the way--", "start": 1661.12, "stop": 1661.404, "duration": 0.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The theory, even if I'm carrying only five photographs or if I'm carrying two letters as was the case in the Chiagles case, for instance, that Judge Cardozo decided in the '20s, they are likely to be very personal, very private photographs.", "start": 1661.404, "stop": 1676.314, "duration": 14.91}, {"text": "So I'm not sure that the expansion of volume increases the invasion of privacy.", "start": 1676.314, "stop": 1680.518, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Dumont, on your argument and on the government's -- the Solicitor General's principal argument, too, a person can be arrested for anything.", "start": 1680.518, "stop": 1688.355, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "A person can be arrested for driving without a seat belt.", "start": 1688.355, "stop": 1691.257, "duration": 2.9}, {"text": "And the police could take that phone and could look at every single e-mail that person has written, including work e-mails, including e-mails to family members, very intimate communications, could look at all that person's bank records, could look at all that person's medical data, could look at that person's calendar, could look at that person's GPS and find out every place that person had been recently because that person was arrested for driving without a seat belt.", "start": 1691.257, "stop": 1723.445, "duration": 32.19}, {"text": "Now, that strikes me as a very different kind of world than the kind of world that you were describing where somebody has pictures of their family in a billfold.", "start": 1723.445, "stop": 1733.135, "duration": 9.69}, {"text": "Doesn't it strike you that way?", "start": 1733.135, "stop": 1734.385, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think the answer that one can always think of marginal cases where there might be concern.", "start": 1734.385, "stop": 1739.556, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "It is not the core case, it is not the typical--", "start": 1739.556, "stop": 1741.658, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know why this is a marginal case.", "start": 1741.658, "stop": 1742.674, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It is not the--", "start": 1742.674, "stop": 1743.308, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your argument and the Solicitor General's principal argument applies to any arrest.", "start": 1743.308, "stop": 1749.328, "duration": 6.02}, {"text": "And it applies to everything on a cell phone.", "start": 1749.328, "stop": 1752.297, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "People carry their entire lives on cell phones.", "start": 1752.297, "stop": 1755.666, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "That's not a marginal case.", "start": 1755.666, "stop": 1757.701, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "That's the world we live in, isn't it?", "start": 1757.701, "stop": 1759.453, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--We hear that repeatedly.", "start": 1759.453, "stop": 1760.62, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "The facts of this case are not somebody's entire life on a cell phone.", "start": 1760.62, "stop": 1764.172, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "This cell phone had a handful of contacts.", "start": 1764.172, "stop": 1767.374, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "I don't think it's in the record, but what we understand is there were 250-some odd contacts, there were about 59 photos and there were perhaps 42 videos that ranged from 30 to 45 seconds.", "start": 1767.374, "stop": 1777.931, "duration": 10.56}, {"text": "Maybe a minute each.", "start": 1777.931, "stop": 1778.831, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Court is to make a rule not for this particular case, but for this category of cases.", "start": 1778.831, "stop": 1785.435, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "And I think what Justice Kagan pointed out is very nervous concern.", "start": 1785.435, "stop": 1789.472, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "That is, take an offense like failing to buckle up, even driving under the influence, not gang crimes, which is what we have in this case.", "start": 1789.472, "stop": 1801.88, "duration": 12.41}, {"text": "It's your rule, then, that the cell phone is fair game no matter what the crime, no matter how relatively unimportant the crime.", "start": 1801.88, "stop": 1820.108, "duration": 18.23}, {"text": "Is it all misdemeanors, all misdemeanors and that opens the world to the police.", "start": 1820.108, "stop": 1825.662, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is true that the Court typically and properly, in this area, draws categorical lines and that is what the Court said in Robinson it was doing.", "start": 1825.662, "stop": 1832.832, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "Now, it also is true the Court has repeatedly said that those lines are drawn based on the generality of cases.", "start": 1832.832, "stop": 1839.072, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "They are not drawn based on the marginal case where the hypothetical potential problematic -- and this case is in the heartland.", "start": 1839.072, "stop": 1846.159, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "It's a violent crime.", "start": 1846.159, "stop": 1847.559, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Dumont, I guess what I'm trying to suggest to you is that you call it marginal, but, in fact, most people now do carry their lives on cell phones, and that will only grow every single year as, you know, young people take over the world.", "start": 1847.559, "stop": 1861.685, "duration": 14.13}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 1861.685, "stop": 1862.301, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "I mean, that's not a marginal case.", "start": 1862.301, "stop": 1865.07, "duration": 2.77}, {"text": "That's what -- they're computers.", "start": 1865.07, "stop": 1866.989, "duration": 1.92}, {"text": "They have as much computing capacity as -- as laptops did five years ago.", "start": 1866.989, "stop": 1872.226, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "And -- and everybody under a certain age, let's say under 40, has everything on them.", "start": 1872.226, "stop": 1878.98, "duration": 6.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think you need to look at the generality of cases.", "start": 1878.98, "stop": 1882.765, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "And in the generality of cases, first of all, you will not be dealing with minor crimes.", "start": 1882.765, "stop": 1886.134, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "You'll be dealing with serious crimes.", "start": 1886.134, "stop": 1888.086, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "And second, you'll be dealing with police who are -- undo their job by booking--", "start": 1888.086, "stop": 1891.455, "duration": 3.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you saying we're just resting on the discretion of the officer?", "start": 1891.455, "stop": 1894.74, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "Because if that's so, then that leads to the next question.", "start": 1894.74, "stop": 1899.293, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "Well, if that's so, then we'll get a warrant.", "start": 1899.293, "stop": 1900.643, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I'm saying that you're -- you are trying to draw lines that can be applied by the officer in the field and often when there's not time to get a warrant either because there's a need to know the information now or because--", "start": 1900.643, "stop": 1912.284, "duration": 11.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, let's leave -- let's leave exigent circumstances out of it.", "start": 1912.284, "stop": 1916.505, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "That -- that's an easy case.", "start": 1916.505, "stop": 1918.222, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "You're not arguing for exigent circumstances here.", "start": 1918.222, "stop": 1921.224, "duration": 3}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--What I'd say is that -- to go back to Justice Scalia's point -- our argument is that the same things that Mr. Fisher concedes, the same interests that Mr. Fisher, I think, concedes justify the search of the person and the seizure of the phone, which are the exigent circumstances type arguments.", "start": 1921.224, "stop": 1938.685, "duration": 17.46}, {"text": "In other words, they are the need to protect officer safety and the need to preserve evidence.", "start": 1938.685, "stop": 1942.555, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "And the fact is you don't know with a phone.", "start": 1942.555, "stop": 1944.922, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "The officer doesn't know with a phone whether there's a safety concern or whether there's an evidentiary concern without looking at the phone.", "start": 1944.922, "stop": 1950.909, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Have there ever been -- is there any basis for the generality that there's a safety concern?", "start": 1950.909, "stop": 1954.88, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "Do you have a case where the -- certainly not where the phone exploded, but when the phone was used to trigger a device or anything like that?", "start": 1954.88, "stop": 1961.367, "duration": 6.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "We don't have a specific case.", "start": 1961.367, "stop": 1963.553, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "What I can point you to--", "start": 1963.553, "stop": 1964.469, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have a general case?", "start": 1964.469, "stop": 1965.103, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, I can point you to, here's a case from California.", "start": 1965.103, "stop": 1967.355, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "I don't think it's cited in the briefs.", "start": 1967.355, "stop": 1968.438, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "It's called Natoli.", "start": 1968.438, "stop": 1969.723, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "There's one where there's a late night arrest.", "start": 1969.723, "stop": 1972.325, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "It -- it starts with a speeding ticket, and it -- off the highway late at night.", "start": 1972.325, "stop": 1977.311, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "It develops that, you know, maybe there's more going on and the person looks to be under the influence.", "start": 1977.311, "stop": 1981.364, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "Taken out of the car.", "start": 1981.364, "stop": 1982.947, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "Then it looks like there might be a gun.", "start": 1982.947, "stop": 1984.299, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "The officer looks at the cell phone.", "start": 1984.299, "stop": 1986.249, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "The first thing he sees when he turns the phone on is a picture of what appears to be the driver standing with two assault rifles, arms akimbo like this, posing with his assault rifles.", "start": 1986.249, "stop": 1996.357, "duration": 10.11}, {"text": "Now, I would say that that changes the situational awareness of the officer in that situation and provides valuable information that was necessary at the time and could not have been gotten later at the station house.", "start": 1996.357, "stop": 2008.098, "duration": 11.74}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What does that have to do with my question about a bomb?", "start": 2008.098, "stop": 2010.95, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm merely saying that it has to do with safety.", "start": 2010.95, "stop": 2014.586, "duration": 3.64}, {"text": "So no, I can't point you to a case where they stopped Timothy McVeigh, looked at his phone and saw some notes about bomb making.", "start": 2014.586, "stop": 2021.422, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "I can't give you that case.", "start": 2021.422, "stop": 2022.507, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I would assume you need to operate the phone to set off the bomb, so that once the police have the phone the bomb is not going to be set off.", "start": 2022.507, "stop": 2030.011, "duration": 7.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is true.", "start": 2030.011, "stop": 2033.397, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "It's also true of all the objects in all the Court's prior cases.", "start": 2033.397, "stop": 2036.699, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "In other words, once in Robinson the police had secured the cigarette pack, there was no question, whether there was a razor blade in it or just heroin--", "start": 2036.699, "stop": 2043.521, "duration": 6.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could I just ask you--", "start": 2043.521, "stop": 2044.821, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--that neither the evidence -- the evidence was not going to be destroyed and the weapon was not going to be used.", "start": 2044.821, "stop": 2046.937, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Could I ask you a question about the extent of your theory?", "start": 2046.937, "stop": 2049.373, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "We're talking about smartphones, which are minicomputers.", "start": 2049.373, "stop": 2052.841, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "But your theory would apply to iPads, computers, anything that's, for example, sitting next to a person in a car, at their desk if they are arrested at their desk, anywhere if they are carrying it in their hand because you see a lot of people carrying the iPad or something comparable, a tablet of some sort.", "start": 2052.841, "stop": 2076.206, "duration": 23.37}, {"text": "Your theory would permit a search of all of those things.", "start": 2076.206, "stop": 2079.842, "duration": 3.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "Our theory extends to objects that are on the person or immediately associated with, for instance in a purse.", "start": 2079.842, "stop": 2085.896, "duration": 6.05}, {"text": "It doesn't necessarily extend to things that are sitting nearby.", "start": 2085.896, "stop": 2089.433, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "The Court has drawn a clear line there.", "start": 2089.433, "stop": 2091.116, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "It's--", "start": 2091.116, "stop": 2091.616, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, how would you?", "start": 2091.616, "stop": 2093.402, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "What is the rule?", "start": 2093.402, "stop": 2094.752, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "You're saying on the person.", "start": 2094.752, "stop": 2096.604, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "Suppose it's in the car in a holder or suppose it's in the passenger's seat?", "start": 2096.604, "stop": 2102.524, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "Are you saying that's -- you don't want to express an opinion about that?", "start": 2102.524, "stop": 2108.844, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "You only want to talk about what's in somebody's pocket?", "start": 2108.844, "stop": 2112.146, "duration": 3.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I'll say I think the Court has drawn different rules for that situation.", "start": 2112.146, "stop": 2115.415, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "If it's on the car seat and if the person's been removed from the car, then under Gant if there's reason to think there might be evidence of the crime of arrest on the phone they can search it and if there's not they can't.", "start": 2115.415, "stop": 2125.023, "duration": 9.61}, {"text": "That's the rule the Court drew, but it's a different rule Under Robinson.", "start": 2125.023, "stop": 2128.741, "duration": 3.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, suppose I'm carrying my laptop in my backpack.", "start": 2128.741, "stop": 2130.843, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if your backpack is on your back when you're arrested, yes, we think that's -- we think that's included.", "start": 2130.843, "stop": 2136.162, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "So let me go back to this volume question, because there are two things about a cell phone that might justify some sort of a special rule.", "start": 2136.162, "stop": 2141.916, "duration": 5.75}, {"text": "There's the volume question and then there's the connectivity and networking question.", "start": 2141.916, "stop": 2147.803, "duration": 5.89}, {"text": "Now, as to the volume question, first of all we don't clearly have it here, but I concede that we could have it in other cases.", "start": 2147.803, "stop": 2153.456, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "And what they seem to be really concerned about is the idea that if you have enough information of enough different kinds on this device and the police spend enough time looking at it, they could build the kind of near-remarkable portrait that some of the Justices alluded to in Gant, or, sorry, in Jones, that -- that really would be qualitatively different from what has ever been done before.", "start": 2153.456, "stop": 2175.556, "duration": 22.1}, {"text": "Now, there are differences from Jones.", "start": 2175.556, "stop": 2177.206, "duration": 1.65}, {"text": "That was government surveillance and this is some choice the person has made to keep a certain amount of information on a phone and then to have it in his pocket.", "start": 2177.206, "stop": 2184.912, "duration": 7.71}, {"text": "We think there's a possibility you could get to that kind of qualitatively different search, but it is miles away from this kind of case and from the heartland case.", "start": 2184.912, "stop": 2192.833, "duration": 7.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "So there are three possibilities: Possibility one, smartphone, no, get a warrant, unless exigent circumstances.", "start": 2192.833, "stop": 2203.805, "duration": 10.97}, {"text": "Possibility two, yes, it's just like a piece of paper that you find in his pocket.", "start": 2203.805, "stop": 2209.959, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "Or possibility three, sometimes yes, sometimes no.", "start": 2209.959, "stop": 2213.83, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "All right, which of those three is yours?", "start": 2213.83, "stop": 2216.163, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "Our possibility -- our position is that the core information like this -- that is contacts, photographs--", "start": 2216.163, "stop": 2222.769, "duration": 6.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, no, I mean of my three choices.", "start": 2222.769, "stop": 2224.103, "duration": 1.33}, {"text": "I mean, call the first choice never except exigent without a warrant; always, you don't need a warrant; or three, somewhere in between.", "start": 2224.103, "stop": 2233.574, "duration": 9.47}, {"text": "Which of the three choices is yours?", "start": 2233.574, "stop": 2235.093, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's in between with an explanation.", "start": 2235.093, "stop": 2236.393, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "In between.", "start": 2236.393, "stop": 2236.743, "duration": 0.35}, {"text": "Okay.", "start": 2236.743, "stop": 2237.112, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "Now we're in between.", "start": 2237.112, "stop": 2237.978, "duration": 0.87}, {"text": "Then I get to my follow up question.", "start": 2237.978, "stop": 2239.645, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "The explanation--", "start": 2239.645, "stop": 2240.064, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "My follow up question is, please tell me what your in-between rule is?", "start": 2240.064, "stop": 2244.949, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Right.", "start": 2244.949, "stop": 2245.968, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "And my in-between rule with the explanation is that for information that is of the same sort that police have always been able to seize from the person, that includes diaries, letters, all other kinds of evidence, purely evidentiary, photographs, address books, for evidence of that same sort, the same rule should apply.", "start": 2245.968, "stop": 2266.982, "duration": 21.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't understand that, Mr. Dumont.", "start": 2266.982, "stop": 2269.583, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "Everything--", "start": 2269.583, "stop": 2269.916, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "The digital format should not make a difference, and I would leave for -- I would leave for a different day -- sorry, but the last explanation to this is I would leave for another case--", "start": 2269.916, "stop": 2275.568, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Mr. Dumont--", "start": 2275.568, "stop": 2276.07, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--the question of whether the volume--", "start": 2276.07, "stop": 2277.603, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 2277.603, "stop": 2277.97, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "Justice Kagan has a question.", "start": 2277.97, "stop": 2279.153, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Mr. Dumont, I guess I just don't understand.", "start": 2279.153, "stop": 2280.536, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "You said if it could be.", "start": 2280.536, "stop": 2282.188, "duration": 1.65}, {"text": "I mean, everything could be reduced to a piece of paper.", "start": 2282.188, "stop": 2284.974, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "All your bank records, you could have them on you.", "start": 2284.974, "stop": 2288.092, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "All your medical records, you could just happen to have them on you.", "start": 2288.092, "stop": 2293.413, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "I mean, that would be so of absolutely everything, wouldn't it?", "start": 2293.413, "stop": 2296.182, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The bank records, of course, the police can get from the bank because they're the bank's records, right, with a subpoena, not with -- not with a search warrant.", "start": 2296.182, "stop": 2304.285, "duration": 8.1}, {"text": "So to the extent that a lot of people--", "start": 2304.285, "stop": 2307.17, "duration": 2.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that the notion that you could get them legally in some other way has never justified an illegal search otherwise.", "start": 2307.17, "stop": 2313.559, "duration": 6.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, but I think it goes to the question of how sensitive is this information that we're being told is now routinely stored on--", "start": 2313.559, "stop": 2320.563, "duration": 7}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your rule is sometimes.", "start": 2320.563, "stop": 2321.997, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "So I say: Sometimes; what's that?", "start": 2321.997, "stop": 2323.682, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "And you say if it is the kind of thing that the police could have searched for if it wasn't on the computer, then they can search for it on the computer.", "start": 2323.682, "stop": 2332.288, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "Now, since they can search for everything in your pockets before when it isn't the computer, then why isn't yours everything?", "start": 2332.288, "stop": 2340.126, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "I mean, by the way, they don't know whether a call is or is not going to turn out to be evidence when it's in your trash box if that's, or wherever you put it, I don't know.", "start": 2340.126, "stop": 2351.699, "duration": 11.57}, {"text": "They don't know that 'til they read it.", "start": 2351.699, "stop": 2353.618, "duration": 1.92}, {"text": "So I guess what you're saying is I thought it was category two, sometimes, but really it's category three, always.", "start": 2353.618, "stop": 2362.474, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "Now, why am I wrong?", "start": 2362.474, "stop": 2364.076, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think he inverted two and three, but--", "start": 2364.076, "stop": 2369.563, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "That gives you time to think.", "start": 2369.563, "stop": 2375.634, "duration": 6.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--If the police are looking for -- have a legitimate investigative purpose, they're looking at the information on the -- to see whether there is evidence of the crime of arrest or of another crime, it seems to us that they should, at a minimum, be able to look at the same kind of information they could have looked at in any other previous context, the address book, the contacts, the phone numbers.", "start": 2375.634, "stop": 2399.332, "duration": 23.7}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So but that's a significant concession on your part, isn't it, because the smartphones carry a lot of information that would not have been the sort of thing police could look at before.", "start": 2399.332, "stop": 2408.021, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "GPS tracking information, the police could never have gotten that before.", "start": 2408.021, "stop": 2411.907, "duration": 3.89}, {"text": "So you are saying that is protected?", "start": 2411.907, "stop": 2413.523, "duration": 1.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not saying it's protected.", "start": 2413.523, "stop": 2415.025, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "I'm saying I think it raises a different set of issues.", "start": 2415.025, "stop": 2416.961, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "It seems to me that in order to try to give some answer to Justice Kagan's concerns that maybe the distinction ought to be between serious and nonserious offenses -- offenses.", "start": 2416.961, "stop": 2431.47, "duration": 14.51}, {"text": "I don't think that exists in our jurisprudence.", "start": 2431.47, "stop": 2433.52, "duration": 2.05}, {"text": "Correct me if I'm wrong.", "start": 2433.52, "stop": 2434.505, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that's correct.", "start": 2434.505, "stop": 2436.955, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "The Court has previously declined to draw that line.", "start": 2436.955, "stop": 2439.824, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "Now, another--", "start": 2439.824, "stop": 2440.409, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "By the way, GPS information, I don't want to admit it, but my wife might put a little note in my pocket,", "start": 2440.409, "stop": 2447.68, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "\"Steven, remember, turn right at the third stoplight, proceed three blocks forward. \"", "start": 2447.68, "stop": 2453.4, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "Of course you could have looked at information that showed where you had been and where you were going as long as it was on paper.", "start": 2453.4, "stop": 2460.654, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "Now it's in a GPS.", "start": 2460.654, "stop": 2462.922, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "So how does your rule help?", "start": 2462.922, "stop": 2465.124, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The GPS would see if he did, in fact, turn right at the thing or had gone somewhere else.", "start": 2465.124, "stop": 2470.011, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think the -- again, we can conceive of situations in which the amount of information and the kind of search would lead to a qualitatively different result.", "start": 2470.011, "stop": 2482.919, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "We think that it--", "start": 2482.919, "stop": 2483.586, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You could amend your answer and it's -- the answers are for you, not for us.", "start": 2483.586, "stop": 2487.89, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "But you could amend your answer to say not just anything that somebody could have had.", "start": 2487.89, "stop": 2493.292, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "The person could have had a diary that records every place the person has ever gone in the last year, it's theoretically possible.", "start": 2493.292, "stop": 2502.065, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "But you could say something that has a realistic analogue in the predigital era.", "start": 2502.065, "stop": 2507.134, "duration": 5.07}, {"text": "We have a similar -- a problem here that's similar to the problem in the Jones GPS case.", "start": 2507.134, "stop": 2512.855, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "You have a rule of law that was established in the predigital era and now you have to apply it in the digital era or you're asked to apply it in the digital era where the technology changes a lot of things.", "start": 2512.855, "stop": 2524.246, "duration": 11.39}, {"text": "But if there is a close analogue in the digital era to something that would have been allowed in the predigital era, that may be a different story.", "start": 2524.246, "stop": 2534.119, "duration": 9.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--We certainly think that's right and we think that that covers, you know, the information that was at issue here, the photographs, the short videos.", "start": 2534.119, "stop": 2541.108, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "It certainly covers address information, contact information, messages, text messages.", "start": 2541.108, "stop": 2547.178, "duration": 6.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But you're not willing to limit -- you're not willing to limit your position to searches that either are in order to protect the officer or in order to preserve evidence or, number three, in order to find evidence of the crime of arrest.", "start": 2547.178, "stop": 2566.923, "duration": 19.74}, {"text": "You're not willing to limit it that way?", "start": 2566.923, "stop": 2569.958, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "You would say whatever is on the person, you can -- you can search.", "start": 2569.958, "stop": 2575.012, "duration": 5.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "We think of the available limits that is by far the best historically based and the most plausible one.", "start": 2575.012, "stop": 2580.316, "duration": 5.3}, {"text": "So to say that -- and because the cases, the old cases, you pointed out that--", "start": 2580.316, "stop": 2584.718, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that gets you into the arrest for, you know, for not wearing a seat belt, and it seems absurd that you should be able to search that person's iPhone.", "start": 2584.718, "stop": 2594.507, "duration": 9.79}, {"text": "And you can avoid that if you -- if you say, look, at the vast majority of cases, this is not going to be a problem, unless the officer can reasonably be looking for evidence of the crime of arrest.", "start": 2594.507, "stop": 2606.831, "duration": 12.32}, {"text": "That will cover the bad cases, but it won't cover the -- you know, the seat belt arrest.", "start": 2606.831, "stop": 2610.949, "duration": 4.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--We think that that could be a perfectly reasonable ruling, and there's precedent in the Court, obviously, for that rule.", "start": 2610.949, "stop": 2616.27, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "There's two things we would say about that.", "start": 2616.27, "stop": 2617.872, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "First, it ought to be an objective standard in line with all of this Court's Fourth Amendment jurisprudence.", "start": 2617.872, "stop": 2622.174, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "It shouldn't depend on what exactly was written down on the -- on the booking sheet.", "start": 2622.174, "stop": 2625.376, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "It should be was there probable cause to arrest or what crimes was there probable cause to arrest for, and it also should include a plain view concept--", "start": 2625.376, "stop": 2635.917, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or how -- there's an analogue with photos.", "start": 2635.917, "stop": 2638.353, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "The arrested person has photos, pre-digital age.", "start": 2638.353, "stop": 2643.588, "duration": 5.24}, {"text": "Of course you can look at them.", "start": 2643.588, "stop": 2645.107, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "On the phone there are photos.", "start": 2645.107, "stop": 2647.641, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "Absolutely analogous, except there are 10,000.", "start": 2647.641, "stop": 2651.443, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "It's indeed his entire life history in photos.", "start": 2651.443, "stop": 2654.645, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--All right.", "start": 2654.645, "stop": 2655.564, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "On your rule, can the policeman look at the photos by analogue or not, because there are 10,000.", "start": 2655.564, "stop": 2663.318, "duration": 7.75}, {"text": "Okay?", "start": 2663.318, "stop": 2663.734, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "What's the answer?", "start": 2663.734, "stop": 2664.42, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "In theory, yes, the police can look.", "start": 2664.42, "stop": 2667.555, "duration": 3.13}, {"text": "In practice--", "start": 2667.555, "stop": 2668.488, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "What we have is, by the way -- you understand where I'm going.", "start": 2668.488, "stop": 2671.674, "duration": 3.19}, {"text": "I think there are very, very few things that you cannot find in analogue to in pre-digital age searches.", "start": 2671.674, "stop": 2681.113, "duration": 9.44}, {"text": "And the problem in almost all instances is quantity and how far afield you're likely to be going.", "start": 2681.113, "stop": 2689.801, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "Why is that your rule?", "start": 2689.801, "stop": 2692.087, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The fundamental doctrinal basis, rational basis of the Robinson rule, I think, is that the fact that arrests -- this is what Justice Powell said and Justice -- well, the fact of the arrest necessarily and legitimately largely abates the privacy interest of the individual and his person and anything he or she has chosen to carry on the person.", "start": 2692.087, "stop": 2715.953, "duration": 23.87}, {"text": "Now, modern technology makes it possible for people to choose to carry a great deal of information.", "start": 2715.953, "stop": 2722.957, "duration": 7}, {"text": "But that doesn't change the fact that the reasonable expectation, if a person is subject to custodial arrest, is that the police will search the person and look at things that they find--", "start": 2722.957, "stop": 2732.647, "duration": 9.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Dumont, is -- are you saying, essentially, that nobody has any expectation of privacy, or that somebody has a dramatically reduced expectation of privacy in anything that the person actually wants to keep on them at all times?", "start": 2732.647, "stop": 2747.157, "duration": 14.51}, {"text": "In other words, one has to keep one's cell phone at home to have an expectation of privacy in it?", "start": 2747.157, "stop": 2751.626, "duration": 4.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Edward C. DuMont", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, we're not saying that at all.", "start": 2751.626, "stop": 2755.094, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "But what we are saying is that people do make choices, and those choices have consequences.", "start": 2755.094, "stop": 2758.882, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "And the consequence of carrying things on your person has always been that if you are arrested, the police will be able to examine that to see if it is evidence of crime.", "start": 2758.882, "stop": 2765.802, "duration": 6.92}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 2765.802, "stop": 2766.936, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "Mr. Dreeben?", "start": 2766.936, "stop": 2770.689, "duration": 3.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 2770.689, "stop": 2775.424, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "I think that it may be helpful to the Court, before exploring possible alternatives to a categorical Robinson rule, to at least briefly understand why there is a categorical Robinson rule and how cell phones implicate many of those concerns.", "start": 2775.424, "stop": 2791.353, "duration": 15.93}, {"text": "The categorical Robinson rule responded to the fact that when a person is carrying something on their person and they are subject to a legitimate probable cause arrest, their expectations of privacy are considerably reduced.", "start": 2791.353, "stop": 2804.594, "duration": 13.24}, {"text": "Not eliminated, but considerably reduced.", "start": 2804.594, "stop": 2807.213, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "And the government, on the other hand, has several very compelling interests at the moment of arrest that are vindicated by conducting a thorough search of the person and the things he has.", "start": 2807.213, "stop": 2818.003, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "It avoids the destruction of evidence.", "start": 2818.003, "stop": 2820.253, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "It protects officer safety.", "start": 2820.253, "stop": 2822.072, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "And it allows the discovery of evidence that's relevant to the crime of arrest to enable prosecution.", "start": 2822.072, "stop": 2827.359, "duration": 5.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But, Mr. Dreeben, if the -- the understanding was, when there's time, get a warrant.", "start": 2827.359, "stop": 2836.732, "duration": 9.37}, {"text": "So here, you can seize the phone and you can secure the phone, and you could go to a magistrate and within an hour get permission to search.", "start": 2836.732, "stop": 2850.741, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "But what is the reason for cutting out the magistrate here?", "start": 2850.741, "stop": 2855.276, "duration": 4.53}, {"text": "It's not -- the instrument itself is not going to be in any danger because the police have taken it and they've disabled it.", "start": 2855.276, "stop": 2861.78, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "So I don't understand why we cut the warrant out of this picture.", "start": 2861.78, "stop": 2866.934, "duration": 5.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So several answers to that, Justice Ginsburg.", "start": 2866.934, "stop": 2869.369, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "The first is that you could probably say the same thing about almost everything that is seized under Robinson and Edwards.", "start": 2869.369, "stop": 2875.607, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "Once it's in the police's hands, they can throw it in the back of the patrol car in the trunk, and it would be safe and they could go get a warrant.", "start": 2875.607, "stop": 2882.863, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "But the balance has always been struck at the moment of arrest to allow the officers to fulfill the compelling interests in the matters that I've previously described.", "start": 2882.863, "stop": 2892.568, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "The second, and I think very critical thing about cell phones is they do differ in the amount of information that a person can carry on them and the amount of revelation about a person's life.", "start": 2892.568, "stop": 2903.959, "duration": 11.39}, {"text": "That is true.", "start": 2903.959, "stop": 2904.842, "duration": 0.88}, {"text": "They also differ in that they greatly facilitate criminal activity.", "start": 2904.842, "stop": 2908.594, "duration": 3.75}, {"text": "They contain a great deal of evidence, and most critically, they are subject to destruction in a way that ordinary physical items are not.", "start": 2908.594, "stop": 2916.434, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "Even if an officer has a cell phone in his hand, he cannot guarantee, unless it's disconnected from the network or somehow protected from the network, that there won't be a remote wipe signal sent to the phone that will wipe its data.", "start": 2916.434, "stop": 2928.825, "duration": 12.39}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have cases where that has happened?", "start": 2928.825, "stop": 2930.426, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have anecdotal reports from the F.B.I. that that has happened, that they have looked into the question of to what extent can you protect a phone through the use of things like Faraday bags.", "start": 2930.426, "stop": 2942.734, "duration": 12.31}, {"text": "I think one of the important things to notice, if you throw a phone into a Faraday bag, which is supposedly going to be able to block network signals, when you open it up, it has to be similarly shielded or it will pick up a signal from a cell tower, and that will wipe the phone.", "start": 2942.734, "stop": 2957.677, "duration": 14.94}, {"text": "And the F.B.I. tried to build a Faraday room in a building that they later discovered Verizon had put up a cell tower on it, and that cell tower put out a strong enough signal to go right through the Faraday room.", "start": 2957.677, "stop": 2969.635, "duration": 11.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "We've had a couple of States where this has been so, where they've had a rule that you can't search, for Michigan, I think, and Vermont.", "start": 2969.635, "stop": 2976.722, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "And are there any instance out of those States where these scenarios have taken place?", "start": 2976.722, "stop": 2983.811, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "I can't speak, Justice Breyer, for the experience in those States.", "start": 2983.811, "stop": 2986.513, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't know then.", "start": 2986.513, "stop": 2986.846, "duration": 0.33}, {"text": "I take it you don't know.", "start": 2986.846, "stop": 2987.996, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't have any access to the information about that.", "start": 2987.996, "stop": 2989.179, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2989.179, "stop": 2989.462, "duration": 0.28}, {"text": "So isn't this a problem that might be postponed because we have warring technologies, et cetera?", "start": 2989.462, "stop": 2996.935, "duration": 7.47}, {"text": "And is it -- you're saying now we should allow searches of all cell phones because there might be a technology that hasn't yet in fact been used in any of the States that have this rule.", "start": 2996.935, "stop": 3008.825, "duration": 11.89}, {"text": "That sounds a little hypothetical.", "start": 3008.825, "stop": 3011.944, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "I'm not quite sure how to handle it.", "start": 3011.944, "stop": 3013.394, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that there is clearly the technology available and growing technology to wipe phones remotely.", "start": 3013.394, "stop": 3021.067, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "But the other critical problem that comes back to Justice Ginsburg's point about getting a warrant is encryption technology is increasingly being deployed in cell phones.", "start": 3021.067, "stop": 3030.339, "duration": 9.27}, {"text": "That is something that clearly is on the rise.", "start": 3030.339, "stop": 3032.358, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "And when a phone is turned off or the lock kicks in and the phone encrypts, it can be almost impossible to get into it.", "start": 3032.358, "stop": 3040.029, "duration": 7.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "How about putting -- let me stop you, because you were making that argument in your brief, and I have three related questions.", "start": 3040.029, "stop": 3045.766, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "Okay?", "start": 3045.766, "stop": 3046.166, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "Why can't you just put the phone on airplane mode?", "start": 3046.166, "stop": 3049.235, "duration": 3.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can I answer that one first?", "start": 3049.235, "stop": 3051.336, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3051.336, "stop": 3051.919, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "First of all, it is not always possible to find airplane mode on all the 500, 600 models of phones that are out there.", "start": 3051.919, "stop": 3060.108, "duration": 8.19}, {"text": "The officer has a lot of things to do when he arrests suspects.", "start": 3060.108, "stop": 3063.66, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "Say he arrests five suspects in a car and they each have three cell phones.", "start": 3063.66, "stop": 3067.948, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "Trying to find and put each one of them into airplane mode and then go the further step and--", "start": 3067.948, "stop": 3073.366, "duration": 5.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're -- you're confusing me, because if you haven't searched on the scene, then the wipe is going to happen.", "start": 3073.366, "stop": 3080.272, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "If you've had enough time at the precinct to put it on airplane mode, the wipe hasn't happened.", "start": 3080.272, "stop": 3086.593, "duration": 6.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, that's not necessarily true, Justice Sotomayor.", "start": 3086.593, "stop": 3088.795, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm a little confused about what this argument is.", "start": 3088.795, "stop": 3090.978, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "Either you do it at the scene and you protect the phone--", "start": 3090.978, "stop": 3094.448, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3094.448, "stop": 3094.781, "duration": 0.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--or you do at the station, and you have enough time to get the warrant by putting it on airplane mode.", "start": 3094.781, "stop": 3098.9, "duration": 4.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you don't necessarily have enough time to get the warrant if you do it at the scene.", "start": 3098.9, "stop": 3103.804, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "That -- that's certainly true.", "start": 3103.804, "stop": 3104.954, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "I think even--", "start": 3104.954, "stop": 3105.387, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't disagree.", "start": 3105.387, "stop": 3105.97, "duration": 0.58}, {"text": "Put it on airplane mode.", "start": 3105.97, "stop": 3106.87, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Even if you bring it back -- the assumption that we're going to have airplane mode and that the Court should craft a constitutional rule around airplane mode assumes that cell phones are not going to be able to be used in airplanes in the next five years and that manufacturers will continue to make an easily available button for airplane mode.", "start": 3106.87, "stop": 3122.43, "duration": 15.56}, {"text": "I don't think the Court should found a constitutional ruling on that assumption.", "start": 3122.43, "stop": 3125.799, "duration": 3.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I don't disagree with you, but you're asking us for constitutional principle based on technology that might or might not do something in one or more cases, but not in the general--", "start": 3125.799, "stop": 3138.124, "duration": 12.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think what I'm trying to suggest, Justice Sotomayor, is the traditional justifications for search-incident-to-arrest include the potential for destruction of evidence.", "start": 3138.124, "stop": 3145.278, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "That is very real today.", "start": 3145.278, "stop": 3147.047, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "It's Petitioner who's asking for a new rule.", "start": 3147.047, "stop": 3149.514, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "We're asking for the application of the Robinson rule, and if the Court is not willing to apply the Robinson rule, then primarily, I think the best rule to apply would be the--", "start": 3149.514, "stop": 3158.855, "duration": 9.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but that's not -- that's not quite accurate.", "start": 3158.855, "stop": 3160.722, "duration": 1.87}, {"text": "What would you do under the Robinson rule with an attorney's briefcase?", "start": 3160.722, "stop": 3165.526, "duration": 4.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The attorney's briefcase may present particularized problems because of attorney-client privilege.", "start": 3165.526, "stop": 3171.929, "duration": 6.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- and doesn't that present the exact problem that every cell phone has?", "start": 3171.929, "stop": 3175.647, "duration": 3.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 3175.647, "stop": 3176.666, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "I was referring--", "start": 3176.666, "stop": 3177.849, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "So I don't think that quite works for you.", "start": 3177.849, "stop": 3178.782, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I was referring to the privilege rule.", "start": 3178.782, "stop": 3180.801, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "The lower courts that have looked at it; this Court has not.", "start": 3180.801, "stop": 3183.836, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "Lower courts that have looked at the question have said that if a person is arrested holding a briefcase, the police can open the briefcase, whether locked or unlocked, and look at its contents.", "start": 3183.836, "stop": 3193.292, "duration": 9.46}, {"text": "They can't just go through the contents for prurient interest.", "start": 3193.292, "stop": 3196.327, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "They can look, however, for evidence that's relevant to criminal activity, and they do that in a way that is minimally invasive of privacy.", "start": 3196.327, "stop": 3204.999, "duration": 8.67}, {"text": "They're not just doing it for the sake of doing it.", "start": 3204.999, "stop": 3206.916, "duration": 1.92}, {"text": "They're looking for evidence.", "start": 3206.916, "stop": 3208.301, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the tax return that's on -- some -- some cell phones have tax returns, so you have the tax return of the jaywalker, looking for a crime.", "start": 3208.301, "stop": 3215.888, "duration": 7.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, and I -- and I -- I would acknowledge, Justice Kennedy, that if the Court is looking for a rule that limits the ability of police to search cell phones, because cell phones are different from paper items in some respects, but not all, that the most reasonable rule to apply would be one that says when there is reason to believe that there's evidence of the crime of arrest on the phone, the officers can look for that.", "start": 3215.888, "stop": 3244.307, "duration": 28.42}, {"text": "When there is not, they can't.", "start": 3244.307, "stop": 3246.759, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "That will--", "start": 3246.759, "stop": 3247.476, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can I ask you a question about that, Mr. Dreeben, because given the variety of things that these cell phones have in them, it seems as though that's -- you know, it sounds good as a limiting principle, but it ends up you can imagine in every case that the police could really look at everything.", "start": 3247.476, "stop": 3264.638, "duration": 17.16}, {"text": "So I'll give you an example.", "start": 3264.638, "stop": 3265.471, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "It's sort of like this case.", "start": 3265.471, "stop": 3266.573, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "Somebody is arrested for a gun crime and now we're going to look at all the various things that might be related to a gun crime.", "start": 3266.573, "stop": 3274.011, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "So whether he's bought guns, whether -- you know, what -- what -- whether he's done searches for gun stores.", "start": 3274.011, "stop": 3281.166, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "His e-mails might something say something about gun possession or gun purchase.", "start": 3281.166, "stop": 3285.718, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "He might have photographs of him with a gun.", "start": 3285.718, "stop": 3288.753, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "You know, the whole range of things could relate to that crime, couldn't it?", "start": 3288.753, "stop": 3293.99, "duration": 5.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Kagan, I would acknowledge that your reasoning is correct in certain circumstances and for certain crimes.", "start": 3293.99, "stop": 3302.08, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "It would not be the case for a jaywalking crime or a bar fight or many other of the minor crimes, seat belt violations, that are posited on the other side of the equation for Respondent's or Petitioner's narrower approach to cell phone searches.", "start": 3302.08, "stop": 3318.956, "duration": 16.88}, {"text": "But I do think that a couple of things are worth thinking about.", "start": 3318.956, "stop": 3322.743, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "First, in a serious offense like a firearms offense in this case, a drug offense in Wurie, if the police didn't -- went, got a warrant, they would be looking at all the same things, because the only way to execute the warrant on the phone would be to engage in at least a cursory search of everything on the phone to see whether it related.", "start": 3322.743, "stop": 3340.721, "duration": 17.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they would be looking at the same things, but the whole idea of a warrant is that a neutral magistrate tells you that you can look at those things and has an opportunity to limit it in whatever way the neutral magistrate feels is appropriate--", "start": 3340.721, "stop": 3351.844, "duration": 11.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I--", "start": 3351.844, "stop": 3352.263, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and that's a protection.", "start": 3352.263, "stop": 3353.063, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I -- I'm not sure that I would go so far as to say the neutral magistrate can narrow the warrant in any way that he sees appropriate.", "start": 3353.063, "stop": 3359.95, "duration": 6.89}, {"text": "This Court's decisions in Grubbs and Dalia say that it's not appropriate for the magistrate to prescribe the manner of executing the search.", "start": 3359.95, "stop": 3366.938, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "But I think the more fundamental point, and this is why I tried to start with the basic bedrock of Robinson, is that there is a different balance--", "start": 3366.938, "stop": 3374.026, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Go ahead, please.", "start": 3374.026, "stop": 3375.192, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There is a different balance at the moment of the arrest.", "start": 3375.192, "stop": 3377.661, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "At that moment society's interests are at their apogee in locating evidence relating to the crime of arrest and apprehending related suspects, and the suspect has a highly reduced privacy interest.", "start": 3377.661, "stop": 3390.721, "duration": 13.06}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 3390.721, "stop": 3391.621, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "4 minutes, Mr. Fisher.", "start": 3391.621, "stop": 3393.271, "duration": 1.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Jeffrey L. Fisher", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3393.271, "stop": 3395.873, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "I think I heard about four or five different proposed rules that I want to just go through, each of them, one at a time.", "start": 3395.873, "stop": 3402.027, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "First, the State talked about a, quote, “ fundamentally different rule ”, and I think Justices have already figured out what we say at page 17-18 of our reply brief, which is that would sweep in virtually everything on the phone.", "start": 3402.027, "stop": 3414.586, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "To the extent it wouldn't, you'd have a really difficult struggle on a case-by-case basis to answer the very difficult question whether any particular app had fundamentally different information that existed in the nondigital world.", "start": 3414.586, "stop": 3428.511, "duration": 13.93}, {"text": "I also heard a suggestion, that, well, if a laptop or a smartphone is on somebody's person, that's different than if it's sitting next to them.", "start": 3428.511, "stop": 3437.283, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "That's not correct if what the government says about its Chimel -- about passwords and wiping satisfies Chimel.", "start": 3437.283, "stop": 3444.288, "duration": 7.01}, {"text": "Remember, Chimel gives authority to search and seize without a warrant anything in the grab area if there's a destruction argument.", "start": 3444.288, "stop": 3453.144, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "So the person who's arrested sitting at his desk at the office, reaching area from his computer would be open to a full search under the government's rule.", "start": 3453.144, "stop": 3462.834, "duration": 9.69}, {"text": "There was also discussion about the exigencies at the scene of an arrest, needing to prevent a remote wipe, preventing a password from kicking in.", "start": 3462.834, "stop": 3473.225, "duration": 10.39}, {"text": "The first thing to make sure you understand is those arguments can apply only at the scene.", "start": 3473.225, "stop": 3478.444, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "They don't apply in this case, where an officer takes the phone back to the police station and 2 hours later searches through it as his -- at his leisure.", "start": 3478.444, "stop": 3486.382, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "So all the arguments about at the scene and what the officer needs to be able to do at the scene can be left for another case.", "start": 3486.382, "stop": 3492.953, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "And I think Justice Breyer is exactly right.", "start": 3492.953, "stop": 3494.721, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "At the very best what the government has shown is that there may be certain tightly limited circumstances where exigent circumstances would apply.", "start": 3494.721, "stop": 3502.225, "duration": 7.5}, {"text": "And I want to say a just quick thing on the password question in particular, which we didn't talk about but may come up in the next argument.", "start": 3502.225, "stop": 3508.129, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "Pages 12 to 14 of our reply brief, we outline how highly unusual as a factual matter it would be for a smartphone to be seized while it's still unlocked and for an officer not to be able to address concern at the scene that it might lock later.", "start": 3508.129, "stop": 3523.307, "duration": 15.18}, {"text": "And it's also worth noting that in a footnote we attach, the government is arguing in lower courts that even if it does lock, that the Fifth Amendment does not give the person the opportunity to refuse to divulge the password in -- in response to a warrant.", "start": 3523.307, "stop": 3536.465, "duration": 13.16}, {"text": "So the password argument doesn't have any play if the government wins the argument its making in the lower courts.", "start": 3536.465, "stop": 3542.386, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "Justice Kennedy, you suggested the possibility of distinguishing between serious and nonserious offenses.", "start": 3542.386, "stop": 3547.94, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "I think, with all due respect, this Court's decisions in Robinson and Atwater, where that issues was squarely presented, preclude that kind of a -- a determination for all the reasons the government argued in those cases.", "start": 3547.94, "stop": 3560.581, "duration": 12.64}, {"text": "And then finally, Justice Scalia, you, I think, had mentioned a couple times the Gant principle as applied to this case, evidence that you think you might find on a phone.", "start": 3560.581, "stop": 3569.186, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "Well, there's two profound problems with that.", "start": 3569.186, "stop": 3571.221, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "The first is, as the Court recognized in Kyllo, you need to be sure to protect the amount of privacy people had at the founding.", "start": 3571.221, "stop": 3578.475, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "And as I said in my opening, the fact that somebody might incidentally have an item on his person, even in the rare case, diary or address book, are leagues away from the kind of information people have now that were stored in the home and that were sacrosanct at an arrest, and that's what the thread throughout history says is an arrest cannot be an occasion to do that kind of a search.", "start": 3578.475, "stop": 3600.308, "duration": 21.83}, {"text": "And, Justice Kagan, you're exactly right.", "start": 3600.308, "stop": 3602.325, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "If you run the Gant test through the world of crimes, the government might be able to identify a crime here or there that would be difficult to make an argument about.", "start": 3602.325, "stop": 3610.946, "duration": 8.62}, {"text": "But lots of minor crimes, like speeding, as we point out in our brief, DUI, littering, all kinds of minor crimes, the person can make a fairly convincing argument sometimes that evidence on the phone would be relevant to that crime of arrest.", "start": 3610.946, "stop": 3626.725, "duration": 15.78}, {"text": "And so I think that brings me to where I want to end, which is understanding what the rule the government propounds would do in terms of just ordinary police work.", "start": 3626.725, "stop": 3634.729, "duration": 8}, {"text": "Remember, this case starts with a traffic stop for an expired license plate.", "start": 3634.729, "stop": 3639.616, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "It is everyday police work that traffic stops are the beginning of criminal investigations and a leverage point into searches.", "start": 3639.616, "stop": 3646.62, "duration": 7}, {"text": "If you adopt a rule that says, even a Gant rule, that says if you can make an argument that evidence on the phone would be relevant to the crime of arrest, take the suspended license, you may have an e-mail from the DMV telling you you better come in and renew.", "start": 3646.62, "stop": 3659.943, "duration": 13.32}, {"text": "If that opens up every American's entire life to the police department, not just at the scene but later at the station house and downloaded into their computer forever, I think you will fundamentally have changed the nature of privacy that Americans fought for at the founding of the Republic and that we've enjoyed ever since.", "start": 3659.943, "stop": 3677.755, "duration": 17.81}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 3677.755, "stop": 3678.889, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3678.889, "stop": 3680.207, "duration": 1.32}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - April 29, 2014", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/23588", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear argument next in Case 13-212, United States v. Wurie.", "start": 0, "stop": 5.904, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "Welcome back.", "start": 5.904, "stop": 6.92, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 6.92, "stop": 8.856, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 8.856, "stop": 11.556, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "The facts of this case, United States v. Wurie, I think, illustrate why any categorical rule that would preclude searches of cell phones incident to arrest would be inconsistent with historical practice and detrimental to law enforcement.", "start": 11.556, "stop": 28.417, "duration": 16.86}, {"text": "This is a case where what the officers did was see a phone ringing.", "start": 28.417, "stop": 32.385, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "On the outside screen, the caller was identified as ‶ my house ″.", "start": 32.385, "stop": 36.754, "duration": 4.37}, {"text": "The officers opened up the phone, pressed one button to see that the call came in from ‶ my house ″ and pressed another to see what the phone number was.", "start": 36.754, "stop": 46.562, "duration": 9.81}, {"text": "That's all they did.", "start": 46.562, "stop": 47.879, "duration": 1.32}, {"text": "That kind of a search serves valid, time-honored functions in the search situation of helping to ascertain the identity of the offender.", "start": 47.879, "stop": 56.835, "duration": 8.96}, {"text": "This was a crucial fact because a few minutes later, Wurie lied about where he lived, which was relevant to the police ultimately obtaining a warrant to search his house.", "start": 56.835, "stop": 67.642, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "They didn't know where he was.", "start": 67.642, "stop": 69.108, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "They would not be able to--", "start": 69.108, "stop": 70.327, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not -- I'm not so sure.", "start": 70.327, "stop": 71.594, "duration": 1.27}, {"text": "If he was at the precinct, they could have gotten a warrant, and once he lied about his arrest, they would have known he wasn't living there and would have gotten a warrant.", "start": 71.594, "stop": 83.752, "duration": 12.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Justice Sotomayor, you could almost always say in search-incident-to-arrest cases that the police could have gotten a warrant.", "start": 83.752, "stop": 92.174, "duration": 8.42}, {"text": "It's -- I'm not talking about cases where somebody is carrying a gun and the police take the gun off them and -- and they secure it that way.", "start": 92.174, "stop": 99.347, "duration": 7.17}, {"text": "But in all of the other cases that you could imagine that involve searches for evidence, letters, which occur in the historical cases; billfolds, which have been discussed here, once the officer has it, you could say the officer shouldn't be able to look in it because that could be done under a warrant.", "start": 99.347, "stop": 117.225, "duration": 17.88}, {"text": "There's no time constraint.", "start": 117.225, "stop": 118.508, "duration": 1.28}, {"text": "There's no destruction of evidence constraint.", "start": 118.508, "stop": 120.527, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "Here, in fact, there actually is a destruction-of-evidence threat with respect to the general category of cell phones, and that's what this Court has been asked to look at, the general category, cell phones and smartphones.", "start": 120.527, "stop": 133.501, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "We discussed earlier the threat of remote wiping and whether airplane mode is an effective counter to that.", "start": 133.501, "stop": 140.005, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "There is the other threat that I think is even more critical to law enforcement today, and that is encryption.", "start": 140.005, "stop": 145.225, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "Because if the phone turns off and becomes encrypted, officers can go to the magistrate and ask for a warrant, but it may be months or years or never if they can break through the encryption and actually obtain the evidence.", "start": 145.225, "stop": 159.235, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "So to the extent that the traditional destruction-of-evidence rationale justified the search of a cell phone or justified the search of traditional items, it applies even more strongly with respect to cell phones than it does with most of the items that might be seized from a person.", "start": 159.235, "stop": 174.495, "duration": 15.26}, {"text": "So Wurie, I think--", "start": 174.495, "stop": 176.68, "duration": 2.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Please tell me about encryption, because I know people can encrypt, but I thought they had to do that when they put the information in the phone.", "start": 176.68, "stop": 183.934, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 183.934, "stop": 184.551, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "As best I understand it, Justice Sotomayor, many smartphones today are equipped with built-in encryption.", "start": 184.551, "stop": 192.123, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "Apple has hardware encryption and software encryption.", "start": 192.123, "stop": 196.008, "duration": 3.89}, {"text": "Samsung and HTC and other brands are quickly following with strong encryption.", "start": 196.008, "stop": 201.729, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "The encryption is deployed in a way that if you don't have the key, the data that's on the phone is useless.", "start": 201.729, "stop": 207.566, "duration": 5.84}, {"text": "The key is often stored in memory and it's accessible only when you can get into the phone.", "start": 207.566, "stop": 213.303, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "Now, if the phone is on and functioning because the person has been arrested while they are, for example, making a phone call, you can get access to the phone and you can attempt to get information from the phone without the encryption key being an obstacle.", "start": 213.303, "stop": 226.796, "duration": 13.49}, {"text": "But if the encryption is deployed, that can sometimes be an insuperable barrier even to the manufacturer.", "start": 226.796, "stop": 234.816, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not sure how on the scene the police are going to look at everything in a cell phone anyway.", "start": 234.816, "stop": 238.17, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "They've got to be doing something to save it.", "start": 238.17, "stop": 240.77, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "If the encryption can be--", "start": 240.77, "stop": 242.139, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, no.", "start": 242.139, "stop": 244.158, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "The -- the evidence is -- the information on the phone is encrypted -- this is my understanding, Justice Sotomayor -- but the phone itself has the key to decrypt it because the user obviously wants to get access to the information.", "start": 244.158, "stop": 255.647, "duration": 11.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean, you have a problem.", "start": 255.647, "stop": 256.816, "duration": 1.17}, {"text": "Apparently, neither you nor I actually have this on their phone, as far as I know.", "start": 256.816, "stop": 262.47, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "So I'm imagining something.", "start": 262.47, "stop": 264.821, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "Maybe you have it.", "start": 264.821, "stop": 265.221, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "There is some kind of system that once it goes ‶ bzzz ″, you never can get the stuff again except after eight months, and when this ‶ bzzz ″ happens, is it happens at least ten minutes after the arrest and not before, so the policeman would have time to look at it.", "start": 265.221, "stop": 282.114, "duration": 16.89}, {"text": "But the -- by the time you get to the stationhouse, the ‶ bzzz ″ has already happened, so now nobody else can.", "start": 282.114, "stop": 288.77, "duration": 6.66}, {"text": "Maybe there is such a thing.", "start": 288.77, "stop": 291.222, "duration": 2.45}, {"text": "I've never heard of it before this minute or before the briefs.", "start": 291.222, "stop": 294.674, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "Well, why wouldn't -- you see I'm similarly incredulous about it from my tone of voice because I don't see why somebody who wanted to ‶ bzzz ″ actually to keep the police away wouldn't do it after 30 seconds.", "start": 294.674, "stop": 307.848, "duration": 13.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if you have an iPhone, Justice Breyer, and I don't know what kind of phone that you have--", "start": 307.848, "stop": 312.135, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't either because I can never get into it because of the password.", "start": 312.135, "stop": 315.004, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 315.004, "stop": 316.454, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's encrypted.", "start": 316.454, "stop": 316.87, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "And that's the problem.", "start": 316.87, "stop": 318.472, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "The phones are set up to protect the data and I think this is something also revealing about--", "start": 318.472, "stop": 323.441, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "My point is, somebody who really wants to go to all that trouble will surely have it turn off after 30 seconds and the policeman won't be able to look at it either.", "start": 323.441, "stop": 331.547, "duration": 8.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Not all criminals are so clever that they manage--", "start": 331.547, "stop": 335.918, "duration": 4.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah.", "start": 335.918, "stop": 336.268, "duration": 0.35}, {"text": "Well, but the dim criminal who is thinking about the magistrate at the station but not thinking about the policeman.", "start": 336.268, "stop": 341.322, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "I mean, you see what I'm doing with my questions?", "start": 341.322, "stop": 342.672, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think--", "start": 342.672, "stop": 343.222, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm casting a little cold water on this as a rationale.", "start": 343.222, "stop": 345.79, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yeah.", "start": 345.79, "stop": 346.874, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "And I -- my response to you is that having tried to ascertain the empirical reality of this problem, it is greatly feared by law enforcement.", "start": 346.874, "stop": 356.012, "duration": 9.14}, {"text": "We've documented that by the numerous studies, the National Institute of Standards and Technology study that talks about the grave concerns that encryption's raised.", "start": 356.012, "stop": 364.785, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "It's not the biggest problem if you get the phone in an active state and you can begin to look through it.", "start": 364.785, "stop": 370.841, "duration": 6.06}, {"text": "It does have unpredictable capabilities of becoming encrypted if it's turned off or if certain apps are deployed on it.", "start": 370.841, "stop": 379.697, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "And for that reason--", "start": 379.697, "stop": 381.63, "duration": 1.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But you have to keep the phone going anyway till you can get to a place where you do something with it.", "start": 381.63, "stop": 387.117, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--A lot of these searches occur, Justice Sotomayor, at the side of the road where the officer opens -- in the Riley case, the officer opened the phone right on the heels of the arrest and he immediately saw evidence that the individual was a gang member, something that he hadn't had personal knowledge of before, because every letter K was preceded by a C, which indicated to him it meant Crip killer, which indicated he was a member of the Bloods gang.", "start": 387.117, "stop": 413.001, "duration": 25.88}, {"text": "So it's a very common thing for officers to take advantage of the information that's on a phone just the way that they would take advantage of the information that's on a person to find out who they are dealing with.", "start": 413.001, "stop": 424.226, "duration": 11.23}, {"text": "And I think it was asked in the Riley argument whether there were instances in which phones have been used to trigger dangers.", "start": 424.226, "stop": 430.729, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "And there are instances in which people have used their cell phones right before an arrest to call in a posse of their accomplices to basically attack the police.", "start": 430.729, "stop": 440.601, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "And by looking at the cell phone quickly, if it's available to the -- to the officers, they can look quickly and see if there was a text sent in the last five minutes or a phone call that might actually protect their safety, which is another one of the traditional justifications of search incident to arrest.", "start": 440.601, "stop": 456.613, "duration": 16.01}, {"text": "That this is a categorical exception, as the Court recognized twice last term, both in Maryland v. King decision and in the McNeely decision, the Court recognized that search incident to arrest was a categorical exception to the normal warrant requirement.", "start": 456.613, "stop": 471.289, "duration": 14.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Dreeben, something that you said about the encryption.", "start": 471.289, "stop": 474.741, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "What -- what is the experience of the police?", "start": 474.741, "stop": 479.643, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "Isn't it so that most cell phones when they're found on a person are not open, that -- that they are locked?", "start": 479.643, "stop": 489.834, "duration": 10.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Ginsburg, I would not be able to answer a question about what condition most cell phones are found in.", "start": 489.834, "stop": 499.307, "duration": 9.47}, {"text": "The fact that this issue has arisen repeatedly in cases across the country indicates that at least in a significant number of cases, the phones are not locked and the officers are able to obtain access to the information.", "start": 499.307, "stop": 514.733, "duration": 15.43}, {"text": "Now, if they are not able to obtain access to the information, I want to tie this back to things that could give the Court some comfort if the Court were concerned about the possibility for police searching too much evidence in cell phones that's not relevant to the crime for which the person is arrested or his identity.", "start": 514.733, "stop": 534.63, "duration": 19.9}, {"text": "Now, we talked earlier about the crime of arrest limitation, which I think would screen out a great many, not all, minor crimes.", "start": 534.63, "stop": 543.236, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "The Court has, at least in the Welsh v. Wisconsin case, talking about exigent circumstances justifying an entry into the home, distinguished between serious and minor crimes.", "start": 543.236, "stop": 553.774, "duration": 10.54}, {"text": "That's another possible line that the Court could explore.", "start": 553.774, "stop": 557.162, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "I'm not as much in favor of that one because I do think that the officers have an interest in determining, no matter who they have arrested, who that person is, because the person could pose an unknown threat even if they are stopped only for a traffic violation.", "start": 557.162, "stop": 572.672, "duration": 15.51}, {"text": "Ascertaining their identity through their cell phone is a useful way to do that.", "start": 572.672, "stop": 576.89, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "There are also potential duration limits on a search incident to arrest.", "start": 576.89, "stop": 581.778, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "As its name indicates, it's incident to the arrest, and this Court's decisions have described the lowering or reduction of expectation of privacy of an arrestee as occurring for a reasonable time and to a reasonable extent after the arrest, then other Fourth Amendment doctrines kick in.", "start": 581.778, "stop": 601.022, "duration": 19.24}, {"text": "So to the extent that most of these searches are going to occur either at the scene of the arrest--", "start": 601.022, "stop": 606.243, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Once we put in that limit, you'll just download the phone at the station and everything, their medical records, their tax returns, even when they're not relevant to the crime, will be part of your database.", "start": 606.243, "stop": 617.801, "duration": 11.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Okay.", "start": 617.801, "stop": 618.201, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "Well, that -- that is my last potential limiting principle.", "start": 618.201, "stop": 621.503, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "This Court need not consider in this case the consequences of downloading the entire contents of a cellphone to a UFED, a universal forensic extraction device which the briefs have talked about.", "start": 621.503, "stop": 636.345, "duration": 14.84}, {"text": "That didn't happen in either of these cases.", "start": 636.345, "stop": 638.53, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "These cases involve manual searches of the information that's available to the user of the phone.", "start": 638.53, "stop": 643.434, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "Once the information has been captured into an electronic database separately in an extraction device, there is at least an argument that at that point the evidence is preserved and potentially the warrant requirement would have a different application, at least if the search of that forensic database was going to go beyond ascertaining identity and verifying officer safety considerations.", "start": 643.434, "stop": 667.55, "duration": 24.12}, {"text": "The Court does not need to examine that in this case.", "start": 667.55, "stop": 670.669, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "It may well be that expectations of privacy do not exist as to information that the user himself can quickly access on a phone, the kind of thing the police are likely to look at when they make an arrest because they are interested in developing evidence that relates to the crime, protecting their safety and ascertaining identity.", "start": 670.669, "stop": 689.23, "duration": 18.56}, {"text": "They are not really interested in going through all an arrestee's medical records and photographs and so forth.", "start": 689.23, "stop": 694.201, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your brief suggested a limitation with respect to access to the iCloud.", "start": 694.201, "stop": 699.605, "duration": 5.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 699.605, "stop": 700.555, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you tell me how you tell the difference?", "start": 700.555, "stop": 702.123, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that would be something that officers would have to develop protocols based on changing technology to address.", "start": 702.123, "stop": 709.644, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "We do not claim here the authority to use the phone to access data that is not on the phone, in the cloud, and it may well be that in the future more information will migrate to the cloud, less will be on the phone, and that may shift what the officers can actually do.", "start": 709.644, "stop": 726.505, "duration": 16.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I thought the whole ideas of smartphones, Mr. Dreeben, and increasingly so, was that even the user doesn't know what's on the cloud or not.", "start": 726.505, "stop": 734.944, "duration": 8.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So to the extent that that is true, Justice Kagan, law enforcement officers, to ensure they're complying with the Fourth Amendment, would have to take the phone off the network.", "start": 734.944, "stop": 746.683, "duration": 11.74}, {"text": "And that is best practices.", "start": 746.683, "stop": 749.285, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "It's discussed in all of the forensic manuals that we cited to the Court.", "start": 749.285, "stop": 753.172, "duration": 3.89}, {"text": "You want to take the phone off the network to avoid the remote wiping problem, to avoid corruption of data through new data coming in.", "start": 753.172, "stop": 761.009, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "It's sound forensic practice to do that and it also serves what we think is a limiting principle.", "start": 761.009, "stop": 766.913, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "Again, the Court doesn't have to decide that limiting principle in this case.", "start": 766.913, "stop": 769.698, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "There's no claim that any cloud data was accessed in this case.", "start": 769.698, "stop": 773.15, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "We're only saying that the search-incident-to-arrest doctrine serves a valuable function, serves a particularly valuable function with cellphones, because they are so commonly used as the medium of the commission of crimes.", "start": 773.15, "stop": 784.608, "duration": 11.46}, {"text": "They are carrying the same kind of information that the individual previously would have carried in paper and it seems somehow a little odd to say that because information has migrated from paper onto a smartphone that the officers have a critical need to obtain--", "start": 784.608, "stop": 801.152, "duration": 16.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think it's odd to say that we're living in a -- in a new world.", "start": 801.152, "stop": 805.89, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "Justice Kagan's questions point out the fact that someone arrested for a minor crime has their whole existence exposed on this little device.", "start": 805.89, "stop": 815.062, "duration": 9.17}, {"text": "From your argument, you want us just to adopt a categorical rule, it's in the custody of the police, they can search it.", "start": 815.062, "stop": 822.066, "duration": 7}, {"text": "Do you have -- do you have any limiting principles that we should considerate at all as a fallback position?", "start": 822.066, "stop": 827.72, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, Justice Kennedy, I do.", "start": 827.72, "stop": 829.254, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "The first one that I think has been discussed in both arguments and Justice Scalia has brought it up as well, is that the evidence to be searched, unless there's some exigency, should be relevant to the crime of arrest and the Court can articulate that in a way that would prevent roving searches or speculative searches.", "start": 829.254, "stop": 851.752, "duration": 22.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that -- that was for an expired license.", "start": 851.752, "stop": 853.604, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So I don't think it's necessarily--", "start": 853.604, "stop": 856.656, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--or is it the guns that were under the hood in the other case?", "start": 856.656, "stop": 860.608, "duration": 3.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--In the Riley case, the guns were under the hood and the arresting officers found a green bandana and some red and white Converse shoes, I believe.", "start": 860.608, "stop": 869.897, "duration": 9.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "The crime of arrest was the expired license.", "start": 869.897, "stop": 873.016, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 873.016, "stop": 873.449, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "The crime of arrest was the firearms in Riley.", "start": 873.449, "stop": 875.535, "duration": 2.09}, {"text": "It was only after they found--", "start": 875.535, "stop": 877.386, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, after the stop, yes.", "start": 877.386, "stop": 878.502, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "--the firearms in the impound search did they actually conduct the arrest.", "start": 878.502, "stop": 881.854, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "And at that point the ultimate search that occurred was because there was a known propensity of gang members to document their use of firearms in pictures.", "start": 881.854, "stop": 890.144, "duration": 8.29}, {"text": "And so that's what the arresting officer was looking for.", "start": 890.144, "stop": 893.527, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "It's no different than what he would have looked for on the arrestee's person in his wallet.", "start": 893.527, "stop": 897.564, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "So it wasn't the kind of cloud-based search, search into health records.", "start": 897.564, "stop": 901.883, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "It was a scope-focused search.", "start": 901.883, "stop": 903.952, "duration": 2.07}, {"text": "So I think that there are limiting principles, Justice Kennedy, that you referred to.", "start": 903.952, "stop": 907.187, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "One is when the officer is looking for crime of arrest-related material and there is evidence that can be plausibly said is crime of arrest-related material on the phone, he can look for that.", "start": 907.187, "stop": 918.562, "duration": 11.38}, {"text": "The Court could couple that, if it wasn't satisfied that that was a sufficient limitation, with a scope-based limit which would say that you can't look everywhere on the phone where there's no realistic chance that there's going to be evidence related to the crime of arrest.", "start": 918.562, "stop": 933.404, "duration": 14.84}, {"text": "You can't just rove through the phone.", "start": 933.404, "stop": 935.439, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "You need to keep a scope focus.", "start": 935.439, "stop": 937.375, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "And that can be enforced and would be enforced by defendants, I can assure you, through post hac litigation and suppression.", "start": 937.375, "stop": 943.795, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "And the police would have to conform their conduct to the constraints of the Fourth Amendment in conducting the search.", "start": 943.795, "stop": 949.599, "duration": 5.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "What scope?", "start": 949.599, "stop": 950.366, "duration": 0.77}, {"text": "You can look at e-mails but not something else?", "start": 950.366, "stop": 954.168, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "What would the scope limitation be?", "start": 954.168, "stop": 958.389, "duration": 4.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would depend on the crime.", "start": 958.389, "stop": 959.755, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "So if you were looking for evidence related to the crime of possession of child pornography, you could certainly go through photographs.", "start": 959.755, "stop": 967.827, "duration": 8.07}, {"text": "If you were looking for another crime, potentially drug trafficking, you would look for things like drug ledgers, recent contacts, lists of customers and not necessarily in videos.", "start": 967.827, "stop": 981.152, "duration": 13.33}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's very hard to see how that limit would be applied.", "start": 981.152, "stop": 985.956, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "You can see and the police would be able to articulate why almost every application, every entry on a cellphone would reasonably be anticipated to have evidence of a particular crime.", "start": 985.956, "stop": 997.014, "duration": 11.06}, {"text": "Obviously e-mails, obviously call logs.", "start": 997.014, "stop": 998.964, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "Even, you know, Facebook.", "start": 998.964, "stop": 1001.666, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "If it's a weapons crime, maybe they've got pictures of themselves with guns.", "start": 1001.666, "stop": 1006.37, "duration": 4.7}, {"text": "I mean, I have trouble imagining what application, what entry police could not say it's reasonably likely that there would be evidence of the crime.", "start": 1006.37, "stop": 1015.059, "duration": 8.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, Mr. Chief Justice, to the extent that you think that's an inevitable generalization and there is a certain way of looking at it in which that's correct, then the interposition of a warrant requirement would do nothing because the warrant would say, search the cell phone for evidence related to drug trafficking and then the phone would be searched in exactly that manner.", "start": 1015.059, "stop": 1036.155, "duration": 21.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "The point of a warrant is that a person who is not involved and is objective listens to what the policeman is saying, knowing that sometimes, like me or any other human being, a policeman can get a little carried away.", "start": 1036.155, "stop": 1048.38, "duration": 12.23}, {"text": "So if, in fact, he does show the warrant, that there is this basis, you issue the warrant.", "start": 1048.38, "stop": 1056.469, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "Many, many -- and if he doesn't you don't.", "start": 1056.469, "stop": 1058.836, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "It isn't because they're difficult legal questions.", "start": 1058.836, "stop": 1061.837, "duration": 3}, {"text": "It's just you want that third dispassionate mind to review what the facts are.", "start": 1061.837, "stop": 1066.341, "duration": 4.5}, {"text": "Now, if that's a purpose of having a warrant, how long does it take to get a warrant in the mine run of these cases?", "start": 1066.341, "stop": 1074.947, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "Is it not a matter of hours in most places?", "start": 1074.947, "stop": 1077.649, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "It may be in some places and not in others.", "start": 1077.649, "stop": 1082.368, "duration": 4.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "In some places I'm sure it's difficult.", "start": 1082.368, "stop": 1083.22, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "But I'm saying most places, major cities, et cetera, my guess was -- and I want to be corrected if I'm wrong -- it's a matter of a few hours and you could do it more quickly if you needed to.", "start": 1083.22, "stop": 1094.928, "duration": 11.71}, {"text": "Am I right about that?", "start": 1094.928, "stop": 1096.811, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know that you are, Justice Breyer.", "start": 1096.811, "stop": 1098.729, "duration": 1.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you are in a department that keeps track pretty much.", "start": 1098.729, "stop": 1102.031, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "You're much more expert than I.", "start": 1102.031, "stop": 1104.049, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "And therefore I would like your best guess on the mine run of things of a range of time to get a warrant.", "start": 1104.049, "stop": 1110.787, "duration": 6.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, Justice Breyer, it varies considerably in the 50 States and the Federal Government depending on where you are, the availability of magistrates, the complexity of the case.", "start": 1110.787, "stop": 1120.243, "duration": 9.46}, {"text": "I would differentiate this from the McNeely case, where the Court was pretty confident that you could get a warrant quickly.", "start": 1120.243, "stop": 1126.147, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "The reason that the Court could be pretty confident about that is drunk driving is a very simple crime, and the officer has very simple observations in order to validate it and there are forms that can be prepared to get a warrant.", "start": 1126.147, "stop": 1138.121, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "With the great -- we're talking now about every crime for which people are arrested.", "start": 1138.121, "stop": 1142.941, "duration": 4.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I see your point.", "start": 1142.941, "stop": 1143.658, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the facts are going to be more complicated.", "start": 1143.658, "stop": 1144.876, "duration": 1.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Assume a range.", "start": 1144.876, "stop": 1147.31, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "The question I'm trying to get to is this.", "start": 1147.31, "stop": 1149.345, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "What, from what you've said is the harm in saying, yes, you need a warrant, but remember, there are exigent circumstances?", "start": 1149.345, "stop": 1159.301, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "So where is someone -- the bell rings on the phone.", "start": 1159.301, "stop": 1163.253, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "Depending on the kind of crime, it may be pretty important to let the policeman answer to find out where it's coming from, because it may be other people on the gang who are coming with weapons.", "start": 1163.253, "stop": 1173.894, "duration": 10.64}, {"text": "Or alternatively, if you're right on the technology, it may be someone about to push a buzzer that will erase the information.", "start": 1173.894, "stop": 1182.066, "duration": 8.17}, {"text": "So remember we have the exigent circumstances.", "start": 1182.066, "stop": 1185.451, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "If your view of the technology is right, they will perhaps be used with common sense and caution.", "start": 1185.451, "stop": 1192.705, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "But you don't need a special rule other than the rule, get a warrant.", "start": 1192.705, "stop": 1198.092, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "How will that hurt?", "start": 1198.092, "stop": 1200.378, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is a special rule for the search incident to arrest content.", "start": 1200.378, "stop": 1203.58, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "It's -- we've discussed a variety of special rules, but that rule completely compromises the interests in search incident to arrest, because they have always assumed that the interest in police discovering evidence that could help them in the prosecution, that could protect their safety, and that would avoid destruction is paramount given the reduced expectations of privacy of the arrestee.", "start": 1203.58, "stop": 1227.445, "duration": 23.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can you work with exigent circumstances--", "start": 1227.445, "stop": 1228.611, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1228.611, "stop": 1229.047, "duration": 0.44}, {"text": "And this is why I -- I hope that I can make this clear, because the encryption problem is what makes it impossible for the police to be confident that you can take the time to go and get a warrant and you won't lose the data forever.", "start": 1229.047, "stop": 1241.605, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "Encryption kicks in when the phone is turned to a setting that automatically will occur on most modern cell phones that turns the phone off and then the phone's contents become encrypted and that's when you need the password to open it up.", "start": 1241.605, "stop": 1257.648, "duration": 16.04}, {"text": "And if you don't have that password, you're not going to be able to do it.", "start": 1257.648, "stop": 1261.267, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "And law enforcement's forensic labs aren't going to be able to get around it in -- except with extraordinary efforts and extraordinary time.", "start": 1261.267, "stop": 1269.122, "duration": 7.86}, {"text": "So we're not talking about the difference here between two minutes to get the warrant and looking at the information.", "start": 1269.122, "stop": 1276.026, "duration": 6.9}, {"text": "It may be months if you don't take advantage of looking at it.", "start": 1276.026, "stop": 1279.23, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do you stop it from going off?", "start": 1279.23, "stop": 1280.496, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, it -- I think that one of the interesting things that Petitioner did in the Riley case was append to the back of his brief a couple of pictures of Apple's iPhone 5 on how you could go into the phone, if the phone is configured in the way that it was in the pictures that he took, and disable the auto lock feature.", "start": 1280.496, "stop": 1299.042, "duration": 18.55}, {"text": "What Petitioner did not do was provide similar information for the 500 or so other phones that are on the market and that will be on the market in the coming years so that police officers will be equipped with a manual that will probably be as thick as the New York City telephone book with the various procedures that are needed to prevent any phone from going into an encryption mode and becoming inaccessible.", "start": 1299.042, "stop": 1322.157, "duration": 23.12}, {"text": "They don't know that at the time they seize the phone, Justice Breyer, and that's why exigent circumstances, unless it's done as a categorical rule, because I did not know whether this phone would encrypt, I searched it, unless you do that, then you are basically putting the officers at the mercy of technology, which will increasingly be able to defeat their ability to conduct the kind of routine searches that they have always conducted in the past.", "start": 1322.157, "stop": 1348.39, "duration": 26.23}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they've got their own technological front in this battle, too, and that's -- I mean, to the extent there are flaws in the Faraday bag, I wouldn't be surprised if that's not improved over the next months or years or whatever.", "start": 1348.39, "stop": 1361.048, "duration": 12.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, it's an arms race between the forensic capabilities of law enforcement labs and the abilities of cell phone manufacturers and criminals to devise technologies that will thwart them.", "start": 1361.048, "stop": 1375.042, "duration": 13.99}, {"text": "And they will leapfrog each other at times and there may be periods when law enforcement has the advantage and there may be period where -- periods where those people who want to protect against revelation of data on the phone will succeed.", "start": 1375.042, "stop": 1387.949, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "And my only point here is that it would not be a wise rule for this Court to announce, based on today's technology and reasonable projections of technology, that the police will just easily be able to go and get a warrant, because my experience from the people that I had spoken with is that a lot of phones are arriving at the lab in a locked and encrypted state and it's very tough to deal with that.", "start": 1387.949, "stop": 1410.981, "duration": 23.03}, {"text": "And if the Court does have concerns, as many members of the Court have expressed, about applying, lock stock and barrel, the traditional Robinson rule, there are weigh stations and compromise positions.", "start": 1410.981, "stop": 1422.106, "duration": 11.13}, {"text": "This case, I think, as California pointed out, both this case and Riley, don't really involve totally unpacking somebody's life from their smartphone.", "start": 1422.106, "stop": 1432.561, "duration": 10.45}, {"text": "And I'm not suggesting that the Court should resolve these cases by announcing a rule that's just limited to the facts of the cases.", "start": 1432.561, "stop": 1438.967, "duration": 6.41}, {"text": "But if the Court is looking to preserve some areas for protection, we've talked about limiting the justification for a search, limiting the scope of a search, limiting the duration of a search, and limiting the intensity in the sense of confining it to what can be found manually on the phone.", "start": 1438.967, "stop": 1458.462, "duration": 19.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Do you -- do you see what I was trying to do with the word ‶ exigency ″?", "start": 1458.462, "stop": 1461.481, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "I was trying to figure out if that's a way of dealing with the unknown here, which is your problem.", "start": 1461.481, "stop": 1467.301, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "That if, in fact, technology is such that the policeman, it's really true if he has five minutes to search, he can get this valuable evidence and if the technology is such that it doesn't even give him five minutes, or if it's such that it gives him four or five hours, or if it's such that he can press a button, or if it's the opposite and they can just cough and encrypt it, well, all that will be fed into the word ‶ exigency ″, which we wouldn't have to decide now, but rather, you could make your arguments about the real exigency for preventing the destruction later in the context of -- of what turns out to be the technology of the time.", "start": 1467.301, "stop": 1510.83, "duration": 43.53}, {"text": "That's what was going on.", "start": 1510.83, "stop": 1512.246, "duration": 1.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Breyer, the reason why Robinson adopted a categorical rule is it concluded that such case-by-case adjudication for officers in the field is completely infeasible.", "start": 1512.246, "stop": 1522.471, "duration": 10.22}, {"text": "And when balancing the important law enforcement interests against the reduced expectations of privacy, Robinson struck a categorical balance.", "start": 1522.471, "stop": 1529.975, "duration": 7.5}, {"text": "Reverting to an exigent circumstances analysis here would unstabilize all of the law under Robinson.", "start": 1529.975, "stop": 1536.214, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "How about a plain view analysis?", "start": 1536.214, "stop": 1537.431, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "Turn on the phone, see if there's been a telephone call within a reasonable amount of time of the arrest or -- or any message that was sent at the time of arrest.", "start": 1537.431, "stop": 1553.09, "duration": 15.66}, {"text": "That's sort of a plain view situation.", "start": 1553.09, "stop": 1556.711, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "It would take care of your person with the picture of him or herself with guns.", "start": 1556.711, "stop": 1560.829, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "It would take care of the call to the confederate.", "start": 1560.829, "stop": 1564.548, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "It would take care of the -- of the imminent destruction of the phone.", "start": 1564.548, "stop": 1570.635, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, Justice Sotomayor, I'm not entirely sure how to articulate that principle, but if it fits within the crime of arrest plus identity principle, then I think it would be a reasonable fallback position.", "start": 1570.635, "stop": 1581.427, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "If I could reserve the balance of my time.", "start": 1581.427, "stop": 1582.91, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1582.91, "stop": 1583.545, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "Ms. Mizner.", "start": 1583.545, "stop": 1589.698, "duration": 6.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1589.698, "stop": 1592.734, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "I'd like to first talk about the encryption that we've been discussing.", "start": 1592.734, "stop": 1600.654, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "It's not an issue in this case.", "start": 1600.654, "stop": 1602.673, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "It was not an issue in Riley.", "start": 1602.673, "stop": 1604.108, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "It was not litigated below.", "start": 1604.108, "stop": 1605.825, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "And the government has just now said that there are a lot of phones arriving at a lab in a locked state, but do we know whether they're in a locked state because they were locked at the time that they were seized or did they lock subsequently?", "start": 1605.825, "stop": 1622.487, "duration": 16.66}, {"text": "The number of password-protected phones that are open at the time of arrest is pure speculation.", "start": 1622.487, "stop": 1632.709, "duration": 10.22}, {"text": "And if they're not open at the time of arrest, the government's argument about locking is irrelevant.", "start": 1632.709, "stop": 1638.529, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "The number of password-protected phones that would be inaccessible at a later time is also an unknown and -- and speculative quantity.", "start": 1638.529, "stop": 1651.173, "duration": 12.64}, {"text": "There are devices that can break passwords.", "start": 1651.173, "stop": 1654.708, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "Technology advances on both fronts.", "start": 1654.708, "stop": 1657.077, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "The government has capabilities of breaking the more typical passwords, the four-digit or letter passwords within 15 minutes.", "start": 1657.077, "stop": 1669.65, "duration": 12.57}, {"text": "There are -- you can obtain assistance from manufacturers in obtaining the passwords and ability to--", "start": 1669.65, "stop": 1679.256, "duration": 9.61}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We've -- we've kind of gotten far afield, which I'm sure is not -- may not be fair to Mr. Fisher or Mr. Dumont, we're talking about their case, but in your case why isn't the information in plain view?", "start": 1679.256, "stop": 1691.398, "duration": 12.14}, {"text": "It says, ‶ my house, my home ″.", "start": 1691.398, "stop": 1694.516, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "They look at it, that's what they see.", "start": 1694.516, "stop": 1696.285, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "They don't have to open anything.", "start": 1696.285, "stop": 1697.252, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--They saw the words ‶ my house ″.", "start": 1697.252, "stop": 1700.17, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "They did have to open the phone and access the log to--", "start": 1700.17, "stop": 1704.408, "duration": 4.24}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sure.", "start": 1704.408, "stop": 1704.808, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "But I'm saying do you have -- you have no objection to the ‶ my house ″?", "start": 1704.808, "stop": 1706.874, "duration": 2.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The ‶ my house ″ words were in plain view.", "start": 1706.874, "stop": 1709.96, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "And under this Court's doctrine, that's not--", "start": 1709.96, "stop": 1712.994, "duration": 3.03}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I assume that that's -- it says ‶ my house ″ because he's done something with the particular number.", "start": 1712.994, "stop": 1717.881, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "If he didn't, it would be the number itself that would show up, right?", "start": 1717.881, "stop": 1720.417, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes.", "start": 1720.417, "stop": 1721.367, "duration": 0.95}, {"text": "And that's part--", "start": 1721.367, "stop": 1722.269, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And so that would also be in plain view?", "start": 1722.269, "stop": 1723.735, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The number was not in plain view.", "start": 1723.735, "stop": 1725.721, "duration": 1.99}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, no.", "start": 1725.721, "stop": 1726.187, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "But I mean, in a -- in a case in which the user had not coded the particular number, the number would show up, I think, right?", "start": 1726.187, "stop": 1734.327, "duration": 8.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1734.327, "stop": 1734.877, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "And--", "start": 1734.877, "stop": 1735.31, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that would be--", "start": 1735.31, "stop": 1736.06, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And the number would be in plain view.", "start": 1736.06, "stop": 1737.445, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Okay.", "start": 1737.445, "stop": 1737.995, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what makes the -- the privacy interest and the associational interest in simply the call logs, which the government has talked about in Mr. Wurie's case, is that it does contain more than simply the numbers dialed.", "start": 1737.995, "stop": 1756.856, "duration": 18.86}, {"text": "You have the associational information that's created by the user.", "start": 1756.856, "stop": 1761.244, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "In this case, it was linking my house to a particular number.", "start": 1761.244, "stop": 1765.962, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "It can go well beyond that.", "start": 1765.962, "stop": 1767.898, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "You can link names and nicknames to -- and places to a number.", "start": 1767.898, "stop": 1773.718, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "You can link e-mails to a name and a number.", "start": 1773.718, "stop": 1776.004, "duration": 2.29}, {"text": "You can link a relationship to a name and a number.", "start": 1776.004, "stop": 1778.856, "duration": 2.85}, {"text": "Doctor, shrink, mom, dad.", "start": 1778.856, "stop": 1781.558, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "You can link a photograph to a number.", "start": 1781.558, "stop": 1783.724, "duration": 2.17}, {"text": "You can link your number -- you can link it to text messages.", "start": 1783.724, "stop": 1786.962, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "You can link it to other numbers.", "start": 1786.962, "stop": 1789.045, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "So you can provide pattern -- and also patterns of calling that provide additional associational data and could indicate the closeness of a relationship.", "start": 1789.045, "stop": 1797.6, "duration": 8.55}, {"text": "How often calls were made, when are they made, what's the time of the call, when did it start or stop, the length of the call.", "start": 1797.6, "stop": 1804.087, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "You can link notes, either general or about a particular phone call.", "start": 1804.087, "stop": 1808.975, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What do you think, if the phone rings, can the police answer it?", "start": 1808.975, "stop": 1811.327, "duration": 2.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "The cases that have addressed answering the phone have been in the context of search warrants for houses where, as the police are searching the house, the phone has been ringing.", "start": 1811.327, "stop": 1825.337, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "And the courts have said that -- lower courts have said that where answering the phone can be viewed as being within the scope of the search warrant, it is permissible for the police to answer the phone.", "start": 1825.337, "stop": 1838.577, "duration": 13.24}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what about this case where there isn't a search warrant?", "start": 1838.577, "stop": 1841.529, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "They didn't answer the phone.", "start": 1841.529, "stop": 1844.648, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The number's in plain view.", "start": 1844.648, "stop": 1845.198, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "I mean, is answering the phone -- can you do it or not?", "start": 1845.198, "stop": 1851.052, "duration": 5.85}, {"text": "You know what number is calling.", "start": 1851.052, "stop": 1852.754, "duration": 1.7}, {"text": "Is it like someone -- you're conducting a search on the house and somebody knocks on the door?", "start": 1852.754, "stop": 1857.389, "duration": 4.63}, {"text": "You can open the door, right?", "start": 1857.389, "stop": 1858.308, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1858.308, "stop": 1859.941, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "And they perhaps could have answered the phone in this case, but they didn't.", "start": 1859.941, "stop": 1864.462, "duration": 4.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but what is your position?", "start": 1864.462, "stop": 1868.514, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "What is the rule you want us to adopt in response to the Chief Justice's question?", "start": 1868.514, "stop": 1872.082, "duration": 3.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say that they could answer the phone.", "start": 1872.082, "stop": 1877.734, "duration": 5.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under what theory?", "start": 1877.734, "stop": 1880.086, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "I don't disagree with you.", "start": 1880.086, "stop": 1882.554, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "I just want to know what would be your theory, and what's the limitation?", "start": 1882.554, "stop": 1885.573, "duration": 3.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, in the sense it's -- it's plain hearing.", "start": 1885.573, "stop": 1888.275, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "It is a -- an analogue of plain view.", "start": 1888.275, "stop": 1893.595, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "There is nothing particularly private about the ringing.", "start": 1893.595, "stop": 1898.649, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "And if you -- the policeman can answer the phone.", "start": 1898.649, "stop": 1904.117, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "It doesn't mean that the person on the other end has to respond.", "start": 1904.117, "stop": 1907.003, "duration": 2.89}, {"text": "It's--", "start": 1907.003, "stop": 1909.205, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was thinking in terms of reasonable expectation of privacy.", "start": 1909.205, "stop": 1913.073, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "Most people don't pick up other people's phones to answer them unless the phone is lost.", "start": 1913.073, "stop": 1918.894, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "And then you pray the person who found it answers it.", "start": 1918.894, "stop": 1923.448, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 1923.448, "stop": 1924.398, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And perhaps this would be analogous to -- to that.", "start": 1924.398, "stop": 1927.833, "duration": 3.44}, {"text": "So the--", "start": 1927.833, "stop": 1928.419, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So do you think -- it's got nothing to do with plain hearing.", "start": 1928.419, "stop": 1929.885, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "I'm not saying they can't -- obviously they can hear the ring.", "start": 1929.885, "stop": 1932.387, "duration": 2.5}, {"text": "I'm just -- it's a big, different step to answer it.", "start": 1932.387, "stop": 1934.905, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--If the police have seized the phone and they can secure it, pending application for a warrant to engage in a search of its contents, then answering the phone could be viewed as part of -- of securing.", "start": 1934.905, "stop": 1960.806, "duration": 25.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does the owner of a cell phone have a reasonable expectation of privacy in the call log?", "start": 1960.806, "stop": 1965.542, "duration": 4.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1965.542, "stop": 1966.794, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "I believe for the associational data and reasons that I have just articulated, that there is an expectation of privacy in the call log.", "start": 1966.794, "stop": 1976.665, "duration": 9.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the cell phone company has all that information, doesn't it?", "start": 1976.665, "stop": 1979.351, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 1979.351, "stop": 1980.034, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "The cell phone company has--", "start": 1980.034, "stop": 1981.636, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Has the numbers.", "start": 1981.636, "stop": 1982.469, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Has the numbers, but it does not have--", "start": 1982.469, "stop": 1984.103, "duration": 1.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 1984.103, "stop": 1984.921, "duration": 0.82}, {"text": "Does the -- does the owner have a reasonable expectation of privacy in a list of the numbers called?", "start": 1984.921, "stop": 1989.99, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Not in the list of the numbers alone, but the call log is not limited to that list of numbers.", "start": 1989.99, "stop": 1999.781, "duration": 9.79}, {"text": "And your phone bill may not necessarily include, depending on the kind of plan you have, may not include information about the length of the call or--", "start": 1999.781, "stop": 2016.391, "duration": 16.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "The cell phone company won't have information about the length of the call?", "start": 2016.391, "stop": 2019.526, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think it would depend on -- whether they keep that information, it would depend on what kind of plan you have.", "start": 2019.526, "stop": 2024.48, "duration": 4.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, what are we dealing with here?", "start": 2024.48, "stop": 2026.682, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "I know everybody wants to talk about global issues, but what -- what are the -- what information are we talking about in this case?", "start": 2026.682, "stop": 2033.936, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "We have my home, which you said is in plain view, my house, and then you have the call log.", "start": 2033.936, "stop": 2039.59, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "What else do we have?", "start": 2039.59, "stop": 2041.275, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is all that was accessed.", "start": 2041.275, "stop": 2044.044, "duration": 2.77}, {"text": "We're talking about the phone number that allowed the police to get to a particular premises.", "start": 2044.044, "stop": 2051.314, "duration": 7.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if the call log, the numbers called, is not covered by a reasonable expectation of privacy, and my house is not covered by a reasonable expectation of privacy, then where is the search?", "start": 2051.314, "stop": 2064.623, "duration": 13.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- the search is in opening the phone itself, which is covered by a reasonable expectation of privacy.", "start": 2064.623, "stop": 2072.311, "duration": 7.69}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, they could--", "start": 2072.311, "stop": 2073.079, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you could do that and look for a razor blade?", "start": 2073.079, "stop": 2074.229, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "You could -- you are then--", "start": 2074.229, "stop": 2079.383, "duration": 5.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Flip open the old style flip-phone to see if there's something inside?", "start": 2079.383, "stop": 2082.085, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, you could examine it, but that is not going to get you the phone number.", "start": 2082.085, "stop": 2086.804, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "You had to push -- the officer here had to push a button in order to get access to the call logs.", "start": 2086.804, "stop": 2094.243, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "There were two buttons that--", "start": 2094.243, "stop": 2095.427, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "See the recent -- but what is -- where is -- what is the reason -- by pushing the button, you get information that you just told me is not covered by a reasonable expectation of privacy.", "start": 2095.427, "stop": 2104.282, "duration": 8.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No, Justice Alito, I believe I said that the information is covered by a reasonable expectation of privacy because there is associational information that is inputted by the owner of the phone.", "start": 2104.282, "stop": 2116.34, "duration": 12.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but was any of that used here?", "start": 2116.34, "stop": 2117.692, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was the link between my house and the -- and the number, yes, that -- that got them to the premises.", "start": 2117.692, "stop": 2126.964, "duration": 9.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they saw the number -- they saw the phone rang at a particular time, and then if you look at the call log, you can see what call came in at that particular time.", "start": 2126.964, "stop": 2134.635, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "And then you know where the call came from that registered as my house.", "start": 2134.635, "stop": 2139.621, "duration": 4.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you wouldn't know that it was my house absent the information that the owner of the phone had put in.", "start": 2139.621, "stop": 2149.394, "duration": 9.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why -- why is that something -- and maybe I don't understand the facts.", "start": 2149.394, "stop": 2151.596, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "If -- if a phone rang right now and you look at the call log and you see what call came in at 12:13, and you know that the call came from my house, and you see the number from -- of the call that came in at 12:13, wouldn't you know that that was the number from my house?", "start": 2151.596, "stop": 2171.16, "duration": 19.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you wouldn't know from the call log alone without information input by the phone owner on that log that it was my house once they get the number.", "start": 2171.16, "stop": 2181.932, "duration": 10.77}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, if it wasn't -- if it wasn't input, you would have the number itself in plain view.", "start": 2181.932, "stop": 2185.819, "duration": 3.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2185.819, "stop": 2186.502, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "But you would then -- you could go to some kind of reverse directory to get an address.", "start": 2186.502, "stop": 2191.406, "duration": 4.9}, {"text": "But you have no -- what is the reason to believe that that number--", "start": 2191.406, "stop": 2196.794, "duration": 5.39}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "You wouldn't know it was the house.", "start": 2196.794, "stop": 2197.544, "duration": 0.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--has anything to do with the defendant's house.", "start": 2197.544, "stop": 2200.179, "duration": 2.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Can -- can -- can the police search the person's wallet and find an -- an index card with a number, my house?", "start": 2200.179, "stop": 2207.85, "duration": 7.67}, {"text": "Can he do that--", "start": 2207.85, "stop": 2209.118, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "I believe--", "start": 2209.118, "stop": 2211.218, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "--and use the information obtained?", "start": 2211.218, "stop": 2212.654, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I believe that the police can examine the contents of a--", "start": 2212.654, "stop": 2221.175, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Examine the contents of the wallet but not read it?", "start": 2221.175, "stop": 2223.009, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "I -- I don't understand the issue.", "start": 2223.009, "stop": 2225.461, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And--", "start": 2225.461, "stop": 2226.479, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is -- may the police or may not the police examine a wallet, find the number that says my house, and act on that information to investigate the crime?", "start": 2226.479, "stop": 2236.435, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "Yes or no?", "start": 2236.435, "stop": 2237.152, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--This Court has not addressed the reading of information examined in -- in -- in searching for incident to arrest.", "start": 2237.152, "stop": 2251.529, "duration": 14.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it seems to me that it's fairly clear that it's part of the contents that are seized, that are on -- in the possession of the arrestee, and that the police can act on it.", "start": 2251.529, "stop": 2259.367, "duration": 7.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, under the justifications of Chimel and -- which were reiterated in -- in Robinson and in Gant and McNeely, the justifications are officer safety and evidence preservation.", "start": 2259.367, "stop": 2274.727, "duration": 15.36}, {"text": "It doesn't -- which does not necessarily encompass reading.", "start": 2274.727, "stop": 2278.846, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "But to address the case of the cell phone, I don't think you have to resolve whether it's appropriate to read paper documents that you come across in examining a paper or not.", "start": 2278.846, "stop": 2291.589, "duration": 12.74}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but the point is the only -- the only information they got and used was the phone number and address of his house, right?", "start": 2291.589, "stop": 2298.426, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "And -- and that it was his house, right?", "start": 2298.426, "stop": 2301.211, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that--", "start": 2301.211, "stop": 2302.244, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's on your driver's license, isn't it?", "start": 2302.244, "stop": 2303.479, "duration": 1.23}, {"text": "So -- and--", "start": 2303.479, "stop": 2306.265, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your residence is, but this was not -- then they needed his driver's license, which they had.", "start": 2306.265, "stop": 2312.752, "duration": 6.49}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So I guess I'm just trying to see what greater invasion of privacy there was in this case than the police looking at your driver's license when you're carrying it around in your wallet.", "start": 2312.752, "stop": 2322.875, "duration": 10.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because my house may not necessarily be the house in which you reside.", "start": 2322.875, "stop": 2330.897, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "You may have chosen to attach that description--", "start": 2330.897, "stop": 2335.535, "duration": 4.64}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So the problem here was that he called -- he indicated that a number was his house, and it might not have been his house?", "start": 2335.535, "stop": 2341.521, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The problem is that the police searched his phone in order to associate information contained in the phone with what they were able to observe in plain view.", "start": 2341.521, "stop": 2356.381, "duration": 14.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "There had to be two buttons, two buttons.", "start": 2356.381, "stop": 2357.748, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2357.748, "stop": 2358.598, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, was there a claim made in this case that exigent circumstances, destruction of evidence, or officer safety justified the search?", "start": 2358.598, "stop": 2365.887, "duration": 7.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2365.887, "stop": 2366.57, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "No?", "start": 2366.57, "stop": 2367.154, "duration": 0.58}, {"text": "Okay.", "start": 2367.154, "stop": 2367.82, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "So I guess if there is a rule that says you can search phones, then you could do it.", "start": 2367.82, "stop": 2375.676, "duration": 7.86}, {"text": "After all, you might search a phone and come up with an advertisement for a Walt Disney movie, which is perfectly public.", "start": 2375.676, "stop": 2383.365, "duration": 7.69}, {"text": "But if the rule is you can't search phones, then you win, even though in this case they came up with something that was -- is -- is that right or not?", "start": 2383.365, "stop": 2392.887, "duration": 9.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2392.887, "stop": 2394.021, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "So--", "start": 2394.021, "stop": 2395.089, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean, if, in fact, you can search the phone thoroughly for everything in the person's life, they might have come up with something when he was six years old, there is, in fact, a picture of an elephant at the zoo.", "start": 2395.089, "stop": 2404.612, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "Totally public.", "start": 2404.612, "stop": 2406.797, "duration": 2.18}, {"text": "But it would still fall within the rule, which what I thought one of the things we're arguing about in this case.", "start": 2406.797, "stop": 2413.551, "duration": 6.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, Justice Breyer, and we believe that the seize-and-secure rule that we are proposing meets the needs of law enforcement by allowing them to maintain custody of the--", "start": 2413.551, "stop": 2429.827, "duration": 16.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2429.827, "stop": 2430.211, "duration": 0.38}, {"text": "Well, what is your argument for the proposition, look, when you search a phone, sometimes what you come up with is perfectly public information; sometimes what you come up with is private information.", "start": 2430.211, "stop": 2443.57, "duration": 13.36}, {"text": "Now, you want to say the absolute rule should be no.", "start": 2443.57, "stop": 2447.788, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "But what's your argument, rather than trying to say sometimes if you get the private information, no; but if you get the public information, yes, et cetera?", "start": 2447.788, "stop": 2456.978, "duration": 9.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Because everything is so intermingled on a cell phone or a tablet or a computer, you don't know what you're going to be getting when you push those buttons and start rummaging through the digital contents of the phone.", "start": 2456.978, "stop": 2473.19, "duration": 16.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In determining whether the examination of information on a cell phone is -- constitutes a search, what do you think we -- we are doing?", "start": 2473.19, "stop": 2484.897, "duration": 11.71}, {"text": "Are we trying to -- to -- are we answering an empirical question, what is the reasonable expectation of privacy of a -- of a person in 2014 who has a cell phone in his or her -- on his or her person?", "start": 2484.897, "stop": 2500.34, "duration": 15.44}, {"text": "Or are we legislating what we think is a good privacy rule?", "start": 2500.34, "stop": 2505.061, "duration": 4.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think the Court is determining whether or not in 2014 an individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy against government intrusion into a device that carries around an increasingly large percentage of somebody's personal and private information.", "start": 2505.061, "stop": 2527.59, "duration": 22.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2527.59, "stop": 2528.256, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "Well, a lot of that -- part of that is the person must act -- people must actually have that expectation.", "start": 2528.256, "stop": 2531.975, "duration": 3.72}, {"text": "That must be the expectation of people at large in 2014, that they think that everything that's on their cell phones is private, or they think some of the information on the cell phones is private, or they think nothing on the cell phone is private.", "start": 2531.975, "stop": 2547.002, "duration": 15.03}, {"text": "Where do you think we should look to answer that question about what people in 2014 think about that question?", "start": 2547.002, "stop": 2554.424, "duration": 7.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think from the fact that people carry them with them in -- in a pocket or in a purse, that that exhibits an expectation of privacy.", "start": 2554.424, "stop": 2567.398, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "You don't expect people to be rummaging through your pockets or -- or through the items you're carrying.", "start": 2567.398, "stop": 2574.152, "duration": 6.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But why is that so?", "start": 2574.152, "stop": 2574.652, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Cell phones are different.", "start": 2574.652, "stop": 2575.854, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "I'm not going to say for a -- suggest for a second that there are like things that existed in the pre-digital area.", "start": 2575.854, "stop": 2581.575, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "But in the pre-digital era, presumably people didn't have a reasonable expectation of privacy in papers, letters, things like that that they had, of photos in a billfold, numbers, addresses, things that they might -- they might be carrying on their persons.", "start": 2581.575, "stop": 2597.518, "duration": 15.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "You--", "start": 2597.518, "stop": 2599.051, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So how do we determine what the -- what the new expectation of privacy is now?", "start": 2599.051, "stop": 2604.021, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think people did have an expectation of privacy in those items until--", "start": 2604.021, "stop": 2610.325, "duration": 6.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then why was it not a search when -- when you -- you searched the pocket of somebody who was arrested and you found the address of someplace?", "start": 2610.325, "stop": 2617.831, "duration": 7.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I believe it is a search, Justice Alito.", "start": 2617.831, "stop": 2620.366, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "It's a question of whether it is a search that has been justified by an exception to the warrant requirement, the -- the scope -- or the permissible scope of the search incident to arrest.", "start": 2620.366, "stop": 2632.091, "duration": 11.72}, {"text": "It's still a search.", "start": 2632.091, "stop": 2633.208, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2633.208, "stop": 2636.476, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "What was the -- why -- how do we determine whether something has -- somebody has a reasonable expectation of privacy in any category of information that is contained on a cell phone?", "start": 2636.476, "stop": 2646.933, "duration": 10.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because of the interconnectivity of the data, I don't think you can say a person has a reasonable expectation of privacy in this app, but not that app, because you don't know what is linked to any other part of the cell phone.", "start": 2646.933, "stop": 2669.714, "duration": 22.78}, {"text": "So the rule that provides the security that the Fourth Amendment is intended to give an individual would be to say--", "start": 2669.714, "stop": 2681.605, "duration": 11.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are -- are you -- I -- I -- I'm assuming that what you're saying -- you just said it a minute ago -- the Fourth Amendment, the searches incident to arrest are an exception to the Fourth Amendment?", "start": 2681.605, "stop": 2695.098, "duration": 13.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Yes, Justice Sotomayor.", "start": 2695.098, "stop": 2696.564, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "And is it your position, I -- I'm assuming this is what this argument's been about, which is whether we're going to extend that exception of -- the exception of searches incident to arrest to a new category, cell phones--", "start": 2696.564, "stop": 2712.643, "duration": 16.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Whether--", "start": 2712.643, "stop": 2713.41, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--which are different than the traditional item.", "start": 2713.41, "stop": 2715.512, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Whether the scope of a justifiable search incident to arrest is going to include a search of -- of the cell phone.", "start": 2715.512, "stop": 2724.117, "duration": 8.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why do you say they are an exception to the Fourth Amendment?", "start": 2724.117, "stop": 2726.652, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "They just don't violate the Fourth Amendment.", "start": 2726.652, "stop": 2728.385, "duration": 1.73}, {"text": "I mean, the Fourth Amendment covers certain things and it doesn't cover other things.", "start": 2728.385, "stop": 2733.306, "duration": 4.92}, {"text": "The things that it doesn't cover are not -- not -- not exceptions.", "start": 2733.306, "stop": 2737.791, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "They're just things not covered.", "start": 2737.791, "stop": 2738.943, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, this Court has espoused a warrant presumption and has said -- has classified the search-incident-to-arrest exigent circumstances as exceptions to the warrant requirements saying that the preference is for a warrant to be obtained, and under certain well-defined circumstances, we are going to say that you may not.", "start": 2738.943, "stop": 2764.677, "duration": 25.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, but that -- that presumption is -- is simply not -- you don't believe that presumption, do you?", "start": 2764.677, "stop": 2768.146, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do.", "start": 2768.146, "stop": 2769.696, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "There are many more searches conducted without a warrant than with a warrant I -- I bet.", "start": 2769.696, "stop": 2773.783, "duration": 4.09}, {"text": "I mean, any automobile search, any inventory search, any -- any search of -- of businesses.", "start": 2773.783, "stop": 2779.604, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "All sorts of searches are conducted without a warrant.", "start": 2779.604, "stop": 2783.072, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "But you still believe that a warrant is the rule and everything else is the exception.", "start": 2783.072, "stop": 2789.31, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "I think it may be the opposite, actually.", "start": 2789.31, "stop": 2791.578, "duration": 2.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Unless the exceptions have swallowed the rule.", "start": 2791.578, "stop": 2795.297, "duration": 3.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the exceptions, viewing the search-incident-to-arrest exception as having per -- as having limited parameters as the First Circuit did--", "start": 2795.297, "stop": 2814.025, "duration": 18.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "The -- the question is whether it's an unreasonable search, and the warrant clause follows much later.", "start": 2814.025, "stop": 2820.847, "duration": 6.82}, {"text": "The question is: Is this an unreasonable search?", "start": 2820.847, "stop": 2822.847, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But this Court has--", "start": 2822.847, "stop": 2824.549, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what the Constitution provides.", "start": 2824.549, "stop": 2825.466, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--This Court has said in many instances that a search not conducted pursuant to a warrant is unreasonable unless it falls within one of the well-defined exceptions that this Court has recognized to the warrant requirement.", "start": 2825.466, "stop": 2842.528, "duration": 17.06}, {"text": "But--", "start": 2842.528, "stop": 2843.495, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it's a search that's reasonable.", "start": 2843.495, "stop": 2844.713, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "That's not necessarily an exception.", "start": 2844.713, "stop": 2846.213, "duration": 1.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--But in terms of reasonableness, this Court is balancing the intrusion against the individual's interest in privacy--", "start": 2846.213, "stop": 2855.768, "duration": 9.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yeah, and that's the--", "start": 2855.768, "stop": 2856.854, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--a traditional balancing test, and we suggest that -- that balance here supports the seize and secure rule that we are advocating.", "start": 2856.854, "stop": 2866.976, "duration": 10.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--No.", "start": 2866.976, "stop": 2867.393, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "I understand that.", "start": 2867.393, "stop": 2867.793, "duration": 0.4}, {"text": "But that -- that's the question that I was asking before.", "start": 2867.793, "stop": 2870.045, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "Is it a reasonable search or seizure?", "start": 2870.045, "stop": 2872.297, "duration": 2.25}, {"text": "All right.", "start": 2872.297, "stop": 2872.747, "duration": 0.45}, {"text": "So you have to balance the privacy interest versus the law enforcement interest.", "start": 2872.747, "stop": 2877.201, "duration": 4.45}, {"text": "And how do -- how do we find out what the privacy interests are -- what the privacy expectations are, which go into that balance with respect to cell phones in 2014?", "start": 2877.201, "stop": 2889.258, "duration": 12.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, on--", "start": 2889.258, "stop": 2891.375, "duration": 2.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does it matter?", "start": 2891.375, "stop": 2891.993, "duration": 0.62}, {"text": "You think it doesn't matter?", "start": 2891.993, "stop": 2893.36, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "Maybe people feel very strongly every single thing that's in the cell phone is -- is private, or maybe they don't.", "start": 2893.36, "stop": 2899.197, "duration": 5.84}, {"text": "Maybe they think some things are private; some things are not private.", "start": 2899.197, "stop": 2901.999, "duration": 2.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that by virtue of the fact that you carry them around in a generally enclosed container, a pocket, a purse, a briefcase, that that exhibits -- that is an indication that people expect that the cell phone -- that the information contained on their cell phone is private.", "start": 2901.999, "stop": 2925.599, "duration": 23.6}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, as opposed to what?", "start": 2925.599, "stop": 2926.449, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "Carrying it around somewhere other than your pocket?", "start": 2926.449, "stop": 2929.383, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "I mean, do -- do you think there's a difference if it's attached to someone's belt and everybody can see it or if it's in a pocket?", "start": 2929.383, "stop": 2936.472, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2936.472, "stop": 2937.372, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "I believe that because you are carrying it with you, it is -- it's not something that you are exhibiting to the public.", "start": 2937.372, "stop": 2945.095, "duration": 7.72}, {"text": "You're not exhibiting the contents of the phone to the public.", "start": 2945.095, "stop": 2947.88, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Surely it's more private if it's locked in your car or kept in your house.", "start": 2947.88, "stop": 2950.214, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2950.214, "stop": 2951.232, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Carrying it with you in public makes it less private.", "start": 2951.232, "stop": 2952.916, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you're not -- it may be less private, but that doesn't mean that you don't have a reasonable expectation of privacy against people taking it from you and starting to intrude and -- and rummage through its contents.", "start": 2952.916, "stop": 2970.377, "duration": 17.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But then that questions the ability of the police to take the phone.", "start": 2970.377, "stop": 2972.412, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "I thought that that was a given, that incident to the arrest, the police could take the phone.", "start": 2972.412, "stop": 2980.851, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "The question is whether they can search it without a warrant.", "start": 2980.851, "stop": 2984.987, "duration": 4.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Justice Ginsburg.", "start": 2984.987, "stop": 2985.937, "duration": 0.95}, {"text": "I was responding in terms of just a general expectation that people are not going to -- if you -- because you're carrying a phone in public, it doesn't mean that you expect that people are going to walk up and remove it from your belt or remove it from your pocket and start searching its contents.", "start": 2985.937, "stop": 3003.784, "duration": 17.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, you could say the same thing about a cigarette pack that -- that has cocaine in it.", "start": 3003.784, "stop": 3008.353, "duration": 4.57}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or a gun.", "start": 3008.353, "stop": 3009.053, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or -- or a gun.", "start": 3009.053, "stop": 3010.52, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the police may seize and examine those containers--", "start": 3010.52, "stop": 3017.274, "duration": 6.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 3017.274, "stop": 3017.691, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--to see whether or not.", "start": 3017.691, "stop": 3019.126, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And why not the phone.", "start": 3019.126, "stop": 3019.793, "duration": 0.67}, {"text": "That's exactly the question.", "start": 3019.793, "stop": 3020.926, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because--", "start": 3020.926, "stop": 3022.678, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have a reasonable -- our rule has been if you carry it on your person, you ought to know it is subject to seizure and examination, and that's been the rule.", "start": 3022.678, "stop": 3033.22, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's the scope of examination that we -- that is at issue with a cell phone.", "start": 3033.22, "stop": 3036.505, "duration": 3.29}, {"text": "A cell phone is fundamentally different from a cigarette pack.", "start": 3036.505, "stop": 3040.14, "duration": 3.63}, {"text": "You can open the cigarette pack, you see whether or not there is something that is subject to destruction.", "start": 3040.14, "stop": 3048.829, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "But whether there's--", "start": 3048.829, "stop": 3049.98, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you can open the cell phone and see whatever's in it.", "start": 3049.98, "stop": 3052.531, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "So if you carry around a cell phone that isn't encrypted or whatever, you know, you -- you -- you get what you -- what you should have expected.", "start": 3052.531, "stop": 3059.368, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "That's -- that's been the rule.", "start": 3059.368, "stop": 3061.72, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "If you are arrested, we -- we can seize it and examine it.", "start": 3061.72, "stop": 3066.374, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The question is what is the scope of a permissible examination.", "start": 3066.374, "stop": 3071.176, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "And when you're talking about a cigarette pack, you're looking at another physical object.", "start": 3071.176, "stop": 3077.247, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "You're not looking at the contents of somebody's home.", "start": 3077.247, "stop": 3081.634, "duration": 4.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand.", "start": 3081.634, "stop": 3082.134, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "But you -- so you're arguing for a new rule.", "start": 3082.134, "stop": 3083.819, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "The rule right up to now has been you can -- we can seize it.", "start": 3083.819, "stop": 3086.955, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "We can examine it totally.", "start": 3086.955, "stop": 3088.171, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "If it's a book, we can read every page of the book.", "start": 3088.171, "stop": 3090.156, "duration": 1.99}, {"text": "You want a new rule for cell phones, right?", "start": 3090.156, "stop": 3093.358, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "We want a rule that says that you cannot search the contents of the cell phone without a warrant.", "start": 3093.358, "stop": 3100.745, "duration": 7.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "At all?", "start": 3100.745, "stop": 3101.364, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "On -- absent exigent circumstances.", "start": 3101.364, "stop": 3103.847, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "What would be an exigent circumstance where you could search, in your view?", "start": 3103.847, "stop": 3109.384, "duration": 5.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "An exigent circumstance?", "start": 3109.384, "stop": 3112.67, "duration": 3.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said you had -- you are arguing for a flat rule to the police, thou shalt not unless there are exigent circumstances.", "start": 3112.67, "stop": 3123.794, "duration": 11.12}, {"text": "So what would be an exigent circumstance where the police, without getting a warrant, could search the cell phone?", "start": 3123.794, "stop": 3133.851, "duration": 10.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "One would be an example of police are investigating a bombing, a upcoming -- a potential bombing, and they have information that the -- that whoever is going to set off the bomb is going to -- may do it with a cell phone, and he's going to be in a particular place at a particular time.", "start": 3133.851, "stop": 3156.615, "duration": 22.76}, {"text": "You see someone approaching with a cell phone, then suggest that under those circumstances, you could--", "start": 3156.615, "stop": 3161.753, "duration": 5.14}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is kind of--", "start": 3161.753, "stop": 3163.271, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--take whatever measures you needed.", "start": 3163.271, "stop": 3164.171, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "--It's not a bomb, but this a different case.", "start": 3164.171, "stop": 3166.407, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "This is somebody in an area selling drugs where the police have told us they typically use cell phones to arrange the deals and the transfers, and this guy is caught with two cell phones.", "start": 3166.407, "stop": 3175.828, "duration": 9.42}, {"text": "Why would he have two cell phones?", "start": 3175.828, "stop": 3177.012, "duration": 1.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Many people have more than -- have multiple cell phones.", "start": 3177.012, "stop": 3181.832, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "I -- there was no--", "start": 3181.832, "stop": 3183.149, "duration": 1.32}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Really?", "start": 3183.149, "stop": 3183.851, "duration": 0.7}, {"text": "What is -- what is your authority for the statement that many people have multiple cell phones on their person?", "start": 3183.851, "stop": 3190.088, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Just observation.", "start": 3190.088, "stop": 3192.038, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "But--", "start": 3192.038, "stop": 3193.124, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "You've observed different people from the people that I've observed.", "start": 3193.124, "stop": 3199.461, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 3199.461, "stop": 3200.411, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's probably true.", "start": 3200.411, "stop": 3202.413, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Particularly since they're in their pockets, right?", "start": 3202.413, "stop": 3203.963, "duration": 1.55}, {"text": "Well, it -- does -- do you -- is it insignificant, in your view, that the cell phone was a method for which criminal transactions were typically undertaken in this area and that the fellow had two cell phones rather than what I would have thought is the more normal one?", "start": 3203.963, "stop": 3218.136, "duration": 14.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Judith H. Mizner", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3218.136, "stop": 3219.055, "duration": 0.92}, {"text": "I don't believe that that should be a criteria justification for searching either cell phone.", "start": 3219.055, "stop": 3227.009, "duration": 7.95}, {"text": "The -- it may be convenient for the police to get information related to a crime by -- by searching without a warrant, but this Court has said repeatedly that convenience and efficiency don't override individual constitutional rights.", "start": 3227.009, "stop": 3245.873, "duration": 18.86}, {"text": "And sanctioning a general evidence gathering search of the entire contents of his cell phone, given the current expansive nature of those contents is an unwarranted expansion of a traditional search incident to arrest, because we are not talking about the kind of traditional containers that holds limited, finite quantities of -- of usually other objects.", "start": 3245.873, "stop": 3277.844, "duration": 31.97}, {"text": "And there is nothing -- a seize-and-secure rule protects both the individuals' expectations of privacy and security and the government's right to obtain evidence consonant with the protections of the warrant requirement, giving the neutral magistrate an opportunity to determine whether there's probable cause for the search of the cell phone and to define the limits of that search.", "start": 3277.844, "stop": 3309.896, "duration": 32.05}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Dreeben, you have four minutes remaining.", "start": 3309.896, "stop": 3315.8, "duration": 5.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 3315.8, "stop": 3318.919, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "A search incident to arrest has always been considered a reasonable search within the meaning of the Fourth Amendment, and I think this case illustrates why that principle well applies to a cell phone.", "start": 3318.919, "stop": 3328.794, "duration": 9.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "This is a very big confusion of the Fourth Amendment.", "start": 3328.794, "stop": 3332.329, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "The Fourth Amendment doesn't permit reasonable searches without a warrant.", "start": 3332.329, "stop": 3338.649, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "It says you need a warrant for -- we've created exceptions to that, but not because a search is reasonable.", "start": 3338.649, "stop": 3346.421, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "Virtually every search could be reasonable without a warrant.", "start": 3346.421, "stop": 3350.457, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "If you've watched somebody selling drugs, it's very reasonable to go into their house, but absent the exigent circumstance of the drugs disappearing, you can't.", "start": 3350.457, "stop": 3363.198, "duration": 12.74}, {"text": "So I don't talk about reasonable searches.", "start": 3363.198, "stop": 3367.002, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "I talk about--", "start": 3367.002, "stop": 3367.819, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "So Justice Sotomayor, the Fourth Amendment doesn't actually say you do need a warrant.", "start": 3367.819, "stop": 3372.137, "duration": 4.32}, {"text": "It does protect the right against unreasonable seizures, and it describes what warrants must contain.", "start": 3372.137, "stop": 3376.775, "duration": 4.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Antonin Scalia", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the only thing it prohibits is unreasonable seizures.", "start": 3376.775, "stop": 3379.726, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Michael R. Dreeben", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's exactly right.", "start": 3379.726, "stop": 3381.328, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "That's the textual prohibition.", "start": 3381.328, "stop": 3381.744, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "This Court has created language in its jurisprudence that prefers warrants in certain circumstances, but as the Court recognized in McNealey last term and in Maryland v. King, the search incident to arrest doctrine is a categorical exception and this case illustrates why.", "start": 3381.744, "stop": 3399.123, "duration": 17.38}, {"text": "The information that was found on the phone was very time sensitive and important to law enforcement.", "start": 3399.123, "stop": 3405.36, "duration": 6.24}, {"text": "It helped fulfill the typical purposes, the categorical purposes of the search incident to arrest doctrine.", "start": 3405.36, "stop": 3412.364, "duration": 7}, {"text": "It helped verify identity, it helped solve the crime that -- for which the individual was arrested, and it was done in a reasonable and nonintrusive manner.", "start": 3412.364, "stop": 3422.655, "duration": 10.29}, {"text": "There was nothing about this search that exposed reams of private data to view.", "start": 3422.655, "stop": 3427.623, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "To the extent that the data was not in a call log really subject to a reasonable expectation of privacy at all, it was discovered in a search but I think that underscores why the search was limited and reasonable.", "start": 3427.623, "stop": 3440.967, "duration": 13.34}, {"text": "So this case really, I think, exemplifies why a categorical rule that respondent urges in this case would not be appropriate, and we submit that this Court should reverse the Court of Appeals.", "start": 3440.967, "stop": 3454.458, "duration": 13.49}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 3454.458, "stop": 3455.308, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Dreeben.", "start": 3455.308, "stop": 3456.441, "duration": 1.13}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 3456.441, "stop": 3457.51, "duration": 1.07}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Apr 29, 2014", "petitioner": "David Leon Riley", "respondent": "State of California", "docket": "13-132", "citation": "573 US _ (2014)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/573/13-132", "lowerCourt": "", "grantedOn": "Jan 17, 2014", "decidedOn": "Jun 25, 2014", "wikiData": {"title": "Riley v. California", "Litigants": "Riley v. California", "Litigants2": "U.S. v. Wurie", "ArgueDate": "April 29", "ArgueYear": "2014", "DecideDate": "June 25", "DecideYear": "2014", "FullName": "David Leon Riley, Petitioner v. California;<br />United States, Petitioner v. Brima Wurie", "USVol": "573", "USPage": "___", "ParallelCitations": "134 S. Ct. 2473; 189 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 430", "Docket": "13-132", "Docket2": "13-212", "OralArgument": "", "OralReargument": "", "OpinionAnnouncement": "", "Prior": "", "''United States v. Wurie'', 612 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/2009716612pfsupp2d1041701 104] ([[D. Mass.]] 2009); reversed, 728 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20130517070 1] ([[1st Cir.]] 2013); cert. granted, {{ussc|71|1161|2014|el": "no}}.", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "Police generally may not, without a [[search warrant|warrant]], search digital information on a [[cell phone]] seized from an individual who has been arrested.", "SCOTUS": "2010-2016", "Majority": "Roberts", "JoinMajority": "Scalia, Kennedy, Thomas, Ginsburg, Breyer, Sotomayor, Kagan", "Concurrence": "Alito", "LawsApplied": "[[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. IV]]"}}